\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 My father - it was strange. It was rather like possibly a sort of gap year. He\rquote d graduated from Oxford in German and French 
\endash  and, by the way, they both met in Berlin as ex-pats. My mother was au pair to some of the leading Jewish families there, and my father was teaching English at the Berlitz School, so they met there. And then he \endash  it\rquote 
s a bit long question/answer \endash  but he had joined the sort of Army, signed up as an undergrad, to be connected to the Army, because, he said, \'93you could get to ride horses\'94. I\rquote 
ve got a wonderful picture of him riding horses, bareback, with one of his close friends. And then, under Colonialism, there was a suggestion that you could go off to one of these lovely places \endash  it was before the War \endash 
 and he went off to Malta with my mother. They\rquote d married, been married for a year, and they thought they were just going to a lovely Mediterranean place, in a
bout 1938, and he was Head of Supplies. Then, of course, the War came and that was a disaster. Malta was one of the most bombed places in the whole of Europe. He was Head of Supplies. Again, I\rquote ve written an article, it\rquote s called \'93
Hybridity: Birthplace and Naming\'94, about the fact that my second name is \'93Melita\'94, after the Island. I was brought up, for a while, on stories of the horrors. They didn\rquote 
t have food. Nothing. And my mother said she saved a packet of biscuits, and she finally gave it to me when I was 
a year, and I sat on the table and she picked up all the crumbs. She said they would go to this one remaining cinema, and there were just two films there, and whenever there were shots of people eating in a restaurant or something \endash  in this film 
\endash  everybody in the audience would say, \'93Throw us a few crumbs!\'94 So I was brought up, I said, with a wonderful hybrid Maltese identity, which I\rquote ve written in The Journal of Mediterranean Studies. And my Maltese connection continues. I
\rquote ve lectured in Malta several times, and only two months ago, a Maltese student asked me to be on her Open University Post-Grad Committee, because I taught her in Malta. So it continues. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
