\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Nothing. No. Because then - and again, I haven\rquote t published this \endash  but I gave a paper in Belfast two years ago. I don
\rquote t know whether it\rquote s a Society, but there\rquote s also a journal about travel, and the theme was \'93traumatic travel\'94, and I gave a paper on my mother\rquote s travel. Because they 
evacuated all British women and children, and my mother, four or five months pregnant, we were put on a plane with other Brits., sent to Cairo. She said there were no seats in the plane, she just sat there, so many months pregnant, with me sitting between
 her legs. The amazing thing is that before I gave the paper, I asked my sister if she had any memories of what my mother said, and my sister produced some tapes, cassettes, where my mother had dictated the journey. I still can\rquote 
t bring myself to listen to t
hose tapes, but this lovely Maltese student says she will listen to them with me. But Elaine, my sister, read out passages, which I put into the paper. We were sent, as evacuees, and my mother apparently went to the hotel kitchen looking helpless, because
 she needed milk for me, and then we were sent, as evacuees, to South Africa, with white Afrikaans families, and my mother and I were called \'93our little evacuees\'94. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
