\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 In in Cape Town. And my mother had no money. The deal of sta
ying in this family was that she had to be out all through the day, so she had to walk the streets - and she said that\rquote s how she got flat feet \endash 
 with me. And then the only free hospital was a Salvation Army Hospital, and she gave birth in the Hospital, and she said they took my sister away, and she thought she was dead, and she didn\rquote 
t know that you get a shuddering thing often, after your second baby, and she lay there totally going \'93Errrrrrrrrrr\'94 like that, nobody to help her. So it was total squalor. Then my father, ironically, was run over by a lorry, the very day that he
\rquote d said goodbye to us at the airport, because there were no lights allowed, and he was run over on his motorbike, and he was then in crutches, and eventually - again, I said I\rquote m living pa
rt on the memories that I was told through my childhood, I don\rquote t have those memories, because my sister\rquote s 18 months younger than me, so you know, it\rquote 
s only 18 months. Eventually he arrived in Durban, in crutches, and I always remember, from childhood, he had a great big brown scar on his leg because of the accident. Then the Brits. - and I could never understand this \endash 
 the Brits. decided, I think because they thought the Afrikaans were going to win the next Election, they decided that all women, all Brits.,
 Anglicans, had to be moved from South Africa. So we went, in a boat, from Durban to Liverpool, during the War, in a convoy. My mother has got a description of 200 women and children in each cell. I think there were nearly 2000 \endash  I\rquote 
ve got the figures somewhere \endash 
 of women and children, with the men in the hold. My father would have just sunk if the boat had gone, because he had leg irons. The ship in front was torpedoed, and the ship behind was torpedoed. And we survived. You know, I went on a trip to South 
Africa with a friend, a sort of SAGA tour, it was all very luxurious, and I stood at the beach, and I was telling the lovely young woman guide, and I said, \'93I\rquote 
ve been on that water, and the ship in front and the ship behind was torpedoed, with the loss of hundreds and hundreds of women and children, and men\'94
. Then we arrived in Liverpool. I said I got the quotes from my sister, [she] had quoted them on the phone, but as I said, I\rquote ve got the cassettes upstairs, but I can\rquote t listen to that as yet, listen to my mother\rquote 
s voice. But when people say, \'93You\rquote re a fucking privileged bourgeois bitch\'94, I think, \'93God! Do you know - \'94 And then my mother described when the boat came into the harbour at Liverpool. She said there was a band to greet them. We
\rquote d been three weeks on that sea. And the Germans had torpedoed all those boats, and we survived. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
