\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Yes. Well, I said this young woman, Sarah, said, \'93Tell me about your grandmother\'94. And I said she couldn\rquote 
t understand this thing that my grandmother was one of 17 children, many of whom died. Her parents had died by the time she was about seven, 
and she was brought up by older brothers. But they were called Stocker, and they owned the kaolin mines in Cornwall, and also something to do with china up in the Midlands, and so it was private enterprise. I had to take over from a colleague who had a co
urse on kinship, in Hull, I had to take over at a month\rquote s notice, and I wasn\rquote t going to do new reading lists or anything, and I decided, in order to have people understand what kinship was, I put up a photograph of my grandmother\rquote 
s wedding, and I said, \'93People say that arranged marriages are just something that happens in Asia\'94. I said, \'93
My grandmother had an arranged marriage. She was white, upper middle-class. She was 18. She was married off, at 18, to a lovely guy, from all I know, called Bradford. A Branston Bradford. And his family were coal and corn merchants\'94
. And she told me, through my childhood, that when she was put on the train, after the marriage, she said to people, \'93I don\rquote t want to go away with this strange man\'94. And she was, apparently, a bril
liant singer, and I think my grandfather got all her money, of course, when she was 21, and he forbade her ever to sing again, because she was a real latent opera singer. It was only years and years later she came to live with us when my mother was widowe
d, and my grandmother was given the heave-ho by her landlord. It\rquote s the bizarre thing of, \'93Here am I, in my property that I own\'94. In those days, the bourgeoisie didn\rquote t invest in property, you rented, and she lived with my mother\rquote 
s nanny. We had a nanny in the family. So my grandmother told me these stories. And then my mother became Head of Old People\rquote 
s Welfare in Hammersmith and she would take my grandmother to some of these social events, and my grandmother, in her sixties. There was a performance going on with kind of Music Hall thing, and my grandmother said, \'93I want to get up and sing\'94
. And my mother said my grandmother got up and sang. She had the most beautiful soprano voice. But she became an alcoholic, apparently, in her twenties. My mother\rquote s memory o
f her was of a total alcoholic. My mother had to go to the bottom of a tree and get my grandmother to climb down in order to come in for supper. Because she disappeared into alcoholism. And so there\rquote 
s the historical position of bourgeois women not being allowed to develop their talents. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
