\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Exactly. I mean, all I knew was that my grandmother was - because my grandmother moved into the middle floor of our hou
se, you see, when my mother was left near destitute \endash 
 my father died of polio. My mother could only get a mortgage because my grandmother would be guarantor, because she had these shares in Bradford and Stocker, so she could be the guarantor. A married woman, a single mother/woman, couldn\rquote 
t get a mortgage, even though my mother had a full-time job. We would hear the noise on the ceiling, and my mother would say, \'93Oh, there\rquote s the old girl boozing at the gin again!\'94 So she was boozing away. And it was only th
anks to this lovely young woman, Sarah, that I put this into a pattern. Then my father\rquote 
s mother was extremely gifted as well. That picture up there, of Cirencester, is the original of her grandfather. He was an artist, and also either him or another grandfather - they were called Beecham \endash 
 they wrote a defining history of Cirencester, and he was interested in the Roman villas in Cirencester. When a friend of mine was doing a painting course in Cirencester, I was going to visit her, and she happened to say, \'93
Oh, a descendant of Beecham is coming to visit me\'94, and they all gasped, and they said, \'93My goodness!\'94, because they have a museum, and so there was that. And my grandmother would - I\rquote 
ve got postcards, somewhere, of his paintings and other things, and she would write, in this spidery thing, \'93The great great grandfather of Judith and Elaine Okely\'94
. But she, in a way like Elizabeth Barrett-Browning, she took to her bed, and so all my memories of her is visiting her and my grandfather in Wimbledon through the
 fifties, and she was lying in the back room, in bed, and my grandfather, who was a civil servant, would just wait on her. And my cousin \endash  that\rquote s my father\rquote s brother\rquote s son \endash 
 I see him every Christmas, we both agreed that we think this was psychosomatic, th
at she was a brilliant, gifted woman, who could never go to university, who read books but like Elizabeth Barrett-Browning, you take to your couch. Ironically, my mother was considered to have gone downwardly mobile in marrying my father! (LAUGHS) I can
\rquote t understand it! Because he didn\rquote 
t come from a family of property! And he was a graduate of Oxford, but that just shows the anti-intellectual streak in British upper class culture. You know, the Queen was taught by somebody who had two years\rquote  training as a n
anny. The Brits, or the English, hate culture. Now, it was only when I thought about it, and was talking to Sarah, and also maybe swapping notes with my cousin up in Edinburgh, that we both agreed that this was psychosomatic. And that\rquote 
s the fate of the upper class woman, or the bourgeois woman. We weren\rquote t aristocracy, they didn\rquote t own land, they were business people, and, you know, I still have money from those Bradford and Son shares. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
