\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 I know! Well, I\rquote 
ve never met the Grandfather Bradford. I did have a lovely picture, or I saw a lovely picture of him in the Corn Market, because he would deal with corn. He was an expert. He\rquote d come with a handful and sell corn, and from my mother\rquote s
 reminiscences, he was a very gifted intelligent man. He was friends with Thomas Hardy. And my mother\rquote 
s memory is being left in the car while Branston went to say hello to Thomas Hardy, leaving my mother in the car, befriending him. And we used to have first editions of all of Thomas Hardy\rquote s books, but again, my mother\rquote 
s brothers are totally anti-intellectual, and God knows what happened to half those things. So from what I can gather, my grandfather was an intelligent man, also a businessman. But those were the days [when] you can\rquote 
t have a woman out of control, singing and getting to be high profile and attracting attention. And my other grandfather, I just have these memories of this tall thin man, very very silent, just serving my grandmother. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
