\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 He was a civil servant. Yeah. But they did have ambitions, because my father won a Scholarship to Dulwich Public School, they weren
\rquote t rolling in money, he won a Scholarship, and my father\rquote s younger brother who \endash  he turned to booze and God knows what \endash 
 and he only died about five or six years ago, but he was eaten up with jealousy and anger, because he said, \'93Do you know, we had to move near Dulwich so that your father could be near the school\'94. He was just eaten up with jealousy, and 
he never went to university, but my father did. Then this is what came out, my father\rquote 
s sister, who died in her nineties, she obviously worshipped my father. And again, here was a very very intelligent woman, a brilliant woman, but there was no way a woman
 could go to university, but her son showed me pictures of my aunt visiting my father in Oxford, and she always kept that by her, and then right by her bedside, she had a photograph, which was the last photograph of my mother, my father, my sister and me,
 in a studio in Lincolnshire. We didn\rquote t know that my father would be dead by the end of the year, with polio. And when I visited her in an Old People\rquote s Home, my cousin hadn\rquote t turned up, and the carers said, \'93Well\'94, you know, 
\'93Paul hasn\rquote t turned up\'94, and I said, \'93Well, Margaret Torn\'e9\'94 \endash  because she married a Belgian miner, by the way \endash  and I went to her room, and I said, \'93Oh, that picture! That\rquote s of me!\'94
 so I could prove my identity. So here\rquote s another woman who\rquote d lost out. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
