\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 I was just at the Elektra stage when my father - after the War he was still in the Army, they didn\rquote t let them free, as it we
re. Then he came back eventually, and we moved into a house that his parents owned in Sussex, near East Grinstead, and he taught in a local school, but he hated it, so eventually he got a job lecturing in French and German at Cranwell, in the RAF, and we 
had one year there. Of course, Lincolnshire was the worst place for polio. But my memory is, through those three or four years before he died, he would sit me on his knee, and he had \endash  and I\rquote ve still got these books somewhere \endash 
 there were French cartoon-lik
e stories for children, and I remember him - I was in awe, because I could see it was French, and he would read out the English, so I understood something about this mystery of translation. Then, in Lincolnshire, we would go for nice long bike rides, just
 the two of us, and it was flat country and there weren\rquote t many cars. Then we were all destined to go on holiday in Cornwall, picking up my mother\rquote 
s mother, who lived in Yeovil, Somerset, on the way. We had a tiny little rented cottage in Lincolnshire, and the night before we \endash  my mother and I, and my sister, I don\rquote t know if my grandmother was with us then or not \endash 
 we had supper, and my father said, \'93Do you know, I feel very stiff. It\rquote s like I\rquote ve got polio\'94. And my mother said, \'93Oh, don\rquote t be silly!\'94 He wasn\rquote t
 going to come with us because he was going to stop off in Wimbledon to see his parents. My last memory is of him standing at the door, in his pyjamas, waving goodbye with his toothbrush \endash  he was just cleaning his teeth \endash 
 you know, I thought I was going to see him in 48 hours. I never saw him again. We got down to Yeovil, and suddenly - I\rquote ve since heard later, that the police turned up at the door at 4 a.m. or something, and they said to my mother, \'93
Your husband has got in hospital, paralysed from the neck down\'94. In those days you had what they called the \'93milk train\'94 - we didn\rquote 
t know any of this, all we knew is that my grandmother and I and my sister and the nanny were there, and they just said, \'93Daddy\rquote s got \lquote flu, so you won\rquote t be able to go on holiday\'94. And
 always mysteriously, my grandmother would shut the door, and talk on the phone in the corridor, every morning, talking to my mother. And do you know, at one point, I actually said to my sister, something like, \'93Daddy\rquote s ill\'94, or \'93Daddy
\rquote s dying\'94, I just picked it up. In the end, after about - maybe that was July/August/ September, you know, we just said, \'93My mother\rquote s ill\'94. We didn\rquote 
t know, my mother, with shock, nearly died of double pneumonia, and she was in the same hospital. And my grandmother \endash  that\rquote s my mother mother \endash  sat Elaine and I down, and just said, \'93Well, Daddy\rquote 
s been ill with polio, but now he\rquote s better, and he\rquote s out of the iron lung, and he\rquote s happy. But you\rquote re going off to boarding school\'94. Which was the school where my mother had been sent. In [earlier] days, women didn\rquote 
t go to school, my mother had a governess until she was 16, and her sisters never went to school. They said, \'93You\rquote re going to your Mummy\rquote s school\'94. And what happened was, my mother had kept in touch with the Headmistress of this s
chool, and incidentally she\rquote d been brilliant at school, but her father made her leave before \lquote A\rquote  Level, the equivalent of \lquote A\rquote  Levels, you know, \'93My daughter\rquote s not going to need any further qualifications\'94
. So we were packed off to boarding school. And the Headmistress had said we could be there free for a term. I kept thinking, \'93Why do we miss our holiday, just because Daddy\rquote s got \lquote flu?\'94
 And you can imagine the guilt that a child would feel later! The anger I feel about it, you know. And then on the hockey pitch, a girl came up to me and said, \'93We\rquote ve been told to be nice to you, because you\rquote re Daddy\rquote s dead\'94
. Can you imagine that! I said, \'93He\rquote s not dead! He\rquote s fine!\'94 And then suddenly, in this terrible regime \endash  and incidentally, my article on the boarding scho
ol is now on the Harvard University reading list in the Psychology Course, because they can\rquote t believe the weirdness of this culture, and it\rquote s also on the \lquote A\rquote  Level in Anthropology now \endash 
 we were suddenly called out of Prep on a Friday, which you never do, because you only see your parents if they visit at the weekend, and we were summoned to the Headmistress\rquote 
s section of the house, and there was my mother, in a suit, all dyed, and I recognised it. You know, children notice these [things]. I said, \'93Mum! Your suit! It was your check suit. Why is it black?\'94 \'93Oh, I like the colour\'94
. And then she sat with us at supper, and I said, \'93You\rquote re wearing Daddy\rquote s ring\'94. \'93Oh, he gave it to me\'94. Then she was staying in a spare room in the Headmistress\rquote s luxury part of the ho
use. Then finally, at about 2.30 on the Sunday I think it was, I was sitting reading the Illustrated London News, and Elaine and I, we were very happy, we\rquote re sitting with our Mum, and my mother just said, \'93I\rquote 
ve got something to tell you. One day Daddy was taken up to Heaven by God\'94. And I remember sort of staring at the Illustrated London News, and then we started crying. And then she had to take the train back to London. I lectured to, it was called \'93
NAGC\'94 \endash  National and Gifted Children\'94 \endash  I was asked to give a lecture, in Oxford, about five years ago, and there were lots of multicultural gifted children, and one young Asian said, \'93When did you become an anthropologist?\'94
 And I said, I said, \'93I\rquote ll tell you when\'94. I said, \'93I went back to the dormitory, eight people in the dormitory, and the great sin was to talk after lights out, and I was sitting there, weeping, on my bed, and the Matron said, \'93
Why are you crying?\'94 \endash  the lights weren\rquote t out then \endash  and I said, \'93My Daddy\rquote s died\'94. And she said, \'93I know. But you\rquote re not to cry, because you\rquote ll keep the other girls awake at night\'94. And I said, 
\'93I think that\rquote s when I became an anthropologist without knowing it. I thought, \lquote I hate this culture\rquote \'94. In my gypsy book - I was taught by Edmund Leach, I dedicated my latest boo
k to Edmund Leach, and he was a student of Malinowski, where you had a holistic view of every society \endash 
 you looked at kinship, beliefs, family, economy, politics, ritual. So I did the standard thing on my gypsy book, and a French anthropologist wrote an amazing book in which, in the first paragraph, he said, \'93It was thanks to Judith Okely\rquote 
s discussion of the death rituals amongst gypsies, that I began to think about my own work on the Manush in France. And until I\rquote d read Okely, I\rquote d never thought about that\'94
. Then he wrote a whole book on the Manush and the dead, and inspired also by a lovely Italian anthropologist. I mean, you could count, on one hand, the number of anthropologists doing gypsies in the whole of Europe. And I began to think, when I reviewed 
his book, \'93Why did I also focus on death?\'94 I thought, \'93Oh yes, holism, ritual\'94. But then I thought, years later, I thought, \'93There\rquote s a psychoanalytical reason\'94
. That I was absolutely mesmerised by the fact that gypsy children were not separated from the knowledge of the death of their parents, and in my article, which I\rquote ve republished \endash  I\rquote ve got photos in my book, The Traveller Gypsies 
\endash  and I never identify the people. I got the photos from the local newspaper offices. It was wonderful, because they were photos taken with consent. They didn\rquote 
t even ask me for money. I could even disguise the name of the newspaper so you didn\rquote t know the area. And there\rquote s one loving picture of a man with his daughters and another man, and I know that that man was dying of a bra
in tumour, and the little happy daughters were aged about seven, and later in the book, I\rquote ve got pictures of his funeral, which I attended, and there\rquote s kids in the front, they\rquote 
re babes in arms, and nothing was hidden from then. And then I\rquote ve got a picture, in the book, of a child throwing earth on to the grave. And so I thought, \'93
Yeah, on psychoanalytical terms, I got fixated, unconsciously, on the link between children\rquote s knowledge of death in another culture\'94. And, of course, the Lady Diana death, that sud
denly blew apart the whole upper class stiff upper lip thing, which the Queen had been brought up to believe in. At my dreaded school, and, of course, because we were there at that school when my father died, the RAF paid. My father was a Socialist, he wo
u
ld never have agreed to us going to this dreaded boarding school! He wanted me to go to Sleaford or Lincoln Grammar School. I do remember he said he wanted me to go to Oxford. So I must have remembered those things. And then at this dreadful school, we we
re all supposed to be debutantes or, you know, elegant ladies. Of course, we didn\rquote 
t have the money, my mother was left with nothing, and no education. She took a degree, part-time, at the LSE, by the way, in sociology and social administration, to the horror of her brothers. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
