\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Well, she was in the WVS as well. She did all that, all voluntary. She was a hive of activity. 
I mean, she had an overactive thyroid, I have an underactive thyroid. Then she was widowed, and my father hadn\rquote t left a Will, so what tiny amount of money he did have, one-third was left to me, one-third to my sister, which we\rquote 
d get when we were 21, and a third to my mother, which was enough for a [house] deposit. She spent the next 20 years paying interest, whereas if she\rquote 
d had the whole money, she could have had the house cash. But she then applied for a job in old people\rquote s welfare in Hammersmith \endash  she saw it advertised \endash  and she got the job, and later, she was told by the councillors, \'93
We knew that as you were a widow, you wouldn\rquote t cause us any trouble because you\rquote d need the job\'94. So then she started getting interested in a social work certificate, and sh
e started going to evening classes. It was like you did an External Degree at the LSE, you hardly went to any lectures, and there was this amazing man called Skidelski, who was a White Russian, who lived in Notting Hill, and in the holidays Elaine and I w
ould sit in the car, and Mum would go and have a tutorial with him. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
