\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
She was absolutely hooked on ethnography, incidentally, and she introduced me to Marsden and The Education and the Working Class. But it was when I was about 15, I said I couldn\rquote t stand the School any more
, and of course, tremendous pressure, because my mother had thought, when she went to the School, she was going to Paradise. Because she\rquote d had [and] her two sisters had the governess, her best friend who\rquote 
d shared the governess with my mother until she was 
12, and then she went to school, [so] my mother was totally isolated. Suddenly she was sent to boarding school, though she said she stood outside the school dining room, was totally terrified to hear 200 voices of children, girls, but for her, it was libe
ration. Although she was shocked because they knew nothing about the Classics. She\rquote d had a brilliant brilliant governess. Now that was another frustrated woman, but who was utterly brilliant, called Kate Nicholson. I\rquote 
ve still got her books. She became my Godmother. God, she was well read! I did meet her. So I said to my mother, \'93I can\rquote t take this\'94. I was weeping, I wasn\rquote t eating, because you weren\rquote 
t allowed to read or do anything. I used to read with a torch under my blankets at night, and I hated sport, so in the end my mother said, \'93Well, take the exam for St. Paul\rquote s\'94
. I took the Entrance Exam, but I realised, talking to the other girls, they\rquote d all been to the Junior - maybe I was 14, 15, I can\rquote t remember \endash  they\rquote d all been to the Junior St. Paul\rquote s School, and they\rquote 
d all been taught a certain syllabus, and the exams were on books I\rquote d never even read. But these people, they\rquote d done a particular era in history, and they were asked questions on that era. We hadn\rquote t been taught that era! So I didn
\rquote t pass. But then the Headmistress said to my mother, they were so impressed, because I had five \lquote O\rquote 
 Levels at the age of 14, and so they would give me a place. Then the School Headmistress summoned me to her office - and that woman only died last May \endash  and she said that I was not to tell my mother this, but I shouldn\rquote t go to St. Paul
\rquote s because it would be very very selfish because my mother wouldn\rquote t be able to do anything in the evenings. Who would look after me when I came back from school? So my reasons for wanting to go to St. Paul\rquote 
s were totally selfish, and I should consider my mother, and I was very lucky that I was being paid for. By this time the Local Authority were paying. It was scandalous! The Middlesex County Council paid, they took over from the RAF! And so the
 woman said, \'93This is our secret\'94, and so I told my mother I wasn\rquote t going to St. Paul\rquote s. Years and years later, I wrote an article which appeared in New Society, called \'93The Girl and her Body\'94 \endash 
 that wonderful editor of New Society, Paul Barker, he loved my article on the boarding school, which he\rquote d seen in proof stage, and he said, \'93Would you write an article for New Society called \lquote The Girl and her Body\rquote ?\'94
 It was a brilliant idea! And it hit the national headlines! It was on the Saturday morning, the weeklies, and I had offers from two publishers to write books on a girls\rquote 
 boarding school, and, of course, I forgot my mother was still contributing to New Society \endash  she was retired by then, it was 1978 \endash  and I remember her sitting, her back to me, digging in the garden, and she said, \'93
You humiliated me. You humiliated me with that article. I did my best, and you got a place in St. Paul\rquote s, and then you suddenly, on a whim, turned it down\'94. Then I told her. I said, \'93The Headmistress told me I\rquote d be selfish if I t
ook up the place\'94. And my mother never said another word. But I know, over the years, she saw \endash  and I don\rquote t want to say too much about this, but my sister is, in the long run, [suffered more than I did]. ... }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
\par 
