\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Well, my sister was also very talented, and people cannot believe this, I\rquote 
ll just say what was said about me. The French mistress \endash  she was English but taught French \endash  the teachers had a wing and tiny little bedsits about half the size of this room, and Miss Lodge, I remember her, she summoned me up, and said, 
\'93Judith, I\rquote d like you to read some more French books\'94, and, \'93You should go to university\'94. And I said, \'93The Headmistress summoned me to the study, only this term\'94 - and that time I had 14 \lquote O\rquote 
 Levels, or 12, something like that, 12 \lquote O\rquote  Levels, I was taking four \lquote A\rquote  Levels \endash  \'93and she said I would be selfish to go to university, I\rquote d be depriving a more worthy person of a place\'94
. And Miss Lodge said, \'93I think you should go to university \endash  but that\rquote s our secret. Don\rquote t tell the Headmistress\'94
. Similarly, my sister, she had a mentor - science, of course, was taught hopelessly at the School, but we had a woman who taught at 
a grammar school, and they brought in grammar school teachers for physics and chemistry, and my sister proved to be brilliant at zoology and biology, and this woman said to Elaine, \'93You should go to university\'94. Then when I was 17/18, you know, I
\rquote d taken my \lquote A\rquote  Levels, and Elaine was obviously lagging behind. Apparently - I\rquote d forgotten this, but my sister, in the middle of a row, suddenly said, \'93You saved me\'94 \endash  this was years later \endash  she said, \'93
You saved me\'94. She said, \'93You wrote a long letter to our mother saying that I must leave the School\'94. And my mother agreed, and my sister went to the Ealing Tech., and she got mega marks, although because she hadn\rquote 
t done Latin, or physics, she couldn\rquote t go to any British university to do zoology. She even got a State Scholarship. But she went to Trinity, Dublin. She was always much better than me at unseen exams, she\rquote s always got top \endash 
 I was hopeless at unseen exams \endash  she got a First Class Degree. She, again, had a wonderful male mentor, and she registered in Imperial C
ollege, and she did a Ph.D. on insects. She did a wonderful thing on the insects that you find on cow pats. She had one of those little things where you puff up and you count the hairs on the back legs of these insects, and she found a different one that 
had extra hairs on its back leg! She\rquote s an amazing one for memory. But again, she was always tormented because the School had always told her that she was no good. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
