\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Well, there are things I won\rquote 
t put on tape. It was lovely when I got this place, the garden was a total wreck and then she redesigned it. She works a tremendous amount. She lives in Exeter. The wonderful thing is that she found a new partner after some years. It was a man she\rquote 
d met in Brazil, and he\rquote s Godfather to my nephew, and she\rquote s Godmother to his son, and then Colin was tragically widowed, and then they got together in about \rquote 96, \rquote 
97, and they live in Exeter. ... And so she came up to do my garden, but unfortunately, because she\rquote s now developed what\rquote s called \'93golf elbow\'94, she can\rquote t do any physical work, and she hasn\rquote t been and done my garden
 for a year, which means it\rquote 
s more tacky! But that was a tremendous bond, because she could use her skills, and then I could also, I hope, pay her pretty generously. ... [Then after our mother died] this thing came out, that I have no memory of! She just said, \'93
You saved me. You saved me. First of all you wrote a letter to Mum, saying I must leave the boarding school\'94, and then she said \endash  and I have no memory of this, it\rquote s just repressed \endash  she said, \'93
Every night, in the dormitory, I would cry, and the only thing would stop me is if the Matron woke you up and brought you, my sister, to my side\'94
. So I realised I became a mother at the age of nine. And that put me off screaming children. Until this lovely boy was born, I hated the sound of babies, crying. And when I saw that lovely little boy, I suddenly thought, you know, \'93He\rquote s in pain
\'94, and my heart melted. But before, I had become a mother at nine. I had to be woken up at night to satisfy this child that was screaming for its mother. And now what could I do? 
So I said that British upper class culture leaves its wounds forever. When my brother-in-law, who was very very upwardly mobile, he thought when he\rquote d got a lot of money, he said he\rquote 
d send his boys to boarding school. My sister threw a fit. She just said, \'93There\rquote s no way. I\rquote m not going to have a job\'94, you know, \'93I\rquote m going to \'85\'94
 And the care and the love she devoted to her boys was just to compensate for the lack of love that she received in our dreadful institution. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 

