\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Well, we became extremely close at the end of her life. It was ironic. The year that my sister married, in \rquote 
76, was the year that I got my first lectureship at Durham, and she also retired. It was a traumatic experience at Durham \endash  I\rquote ve written a whole article on that, called, \'93Gender lessons in ivory towers\'94
, the sexism in Durham was absolutely horrendous! When I went to the library to register \endash  I was 30 \endash  as a member of staff, to get my staff card, I was accused of fraud, that I couldn\rquote 
t possibly be a lecturer, that I was a student, and how dare I cheat and ask for a staff card. And then when I went to the Staff Common Room for eating, I was blocked at the door, saying, \'93We don\rquote t allow students here. Go away\'94
. You know, I was a lecturer! So I had that trauma, but I still hadn\rquote t completed my D.Phil.. And then I spent the summer, after my first year in Durham, I spent the whole summer
 in Cornwall, writing up, finishing up my Ph.D., and my mother would do all the shopping, I\rquote d get my breakfast, and then I\rquote 
d go up to the spare room, and I would write and write and write. And so she identified with a fellow academic. And the other thing I
 remember is that she was always interested in qualitative research in, like Marsden and Jackson. She used to teach - there was a wonderful book about Glasgow, and about the terrible high-rise flats and everything, and the students would love my mother
\rquote s e
mphasis on the minutiae. But she was the only sociologist in the Department, which included medics and psychologists, and the Head of Department was determined to turn it into a Medical School Department, and they rubbished her work. I remember her in tea
rs, at some point \endash  that was before she retired. Because when I first got the job at the Centre for Environmental Studies, after my Cambridge \endash  I did a one-year Conversion Course at Cambridge, in anthropology, that\rquote 
s where I was taught by Edmund Leach. I hadn\rquote t yet bought a house with my then partner, and so I lived in Ealing, in that house, and I would go to Regent\rquote s Park where the offices were, and I would support her because they couldn\rquote 
t understand ethnography. The students all adored her, and she would supervise undergrad dissertations that were qualitative. Then the External Examiner would be a quantitative person, who would say the sample was, you know, \'93you haven\rquote 
t got this, and haven\rquote t done that. This is not scientific\'94. I mean, there weren\rquote t even quantitative sociologists there, it was \'85
 and the students would be failed or given a low mark. And they were brilliant students. So in the end, when the students came and asked to be supervised by her, she said, \'93If you want a good mark, don\rquote t be supervised
 by me, because the External will rubbish it\'94. And she would weep. And then, you know, this same tyrant man, he blocked her promotion up the salary scale, he said that she hadn\rquote t fulfilled enough, and she hadn\rquote 
t got a doctorate, and as you know from Essex,
 many people got jobs then without doctorates. She hoped to do one, but how could she do it with a huge teaching load? And she always had fantasies of doing it. And the Department blocked her going up the salary thing, and saying that she was no good. And
 
fortunately, my mother was able to argue that she taught both sociology and social administration, that she was teaching two disciplines, and she went to the Union, and she jumped the hurdle. But I used to hear these stories, and in the end she took early
 retirement because she couldn\rquote t stand the stress any more. But I do know that there were totally loyal students who adored her, one of whom, in the end, was the husband of the woman that was the psychotherapist that I\rquote 
ve mentioned, she actually said to me when she knew that life was ebbing away, she said, \'93I want Malcolm to speak at my funeral\'94, and he did. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
