\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Well, what she knew was that - she always said to me, \'93
You have to get a training. You have to get a job. You have to get qualifications\'94. She had no idea that the Headmistress was telling me I\rquote d be selfish to go to university. She thought the place encouraged you. And she just said, \'93
Judith, you can\rquote t depend on marriage, because your husband can die or leave you, and you\rquote ll be penniless\'94. And she had this bizarre thing about \endash  because I was terribly interested in fashion \endash  and she said, \'93
Judith, you should be a buyer at Harrods\'94, that was the sort of thing. And then, \'93You must be a secretary\'94, because those were the things. I actually was interviewed for a Secretarial College \endash  Mrs. Hoster\rquote s \endash 
 it was a terribly upper class private place, but fortunately, af
ter leaving school, I - a contemporary of mine, they would go to Paris, usually to learn to speak French in order to go to Finishing School, and in those days, one of my contemporaries, she went to the Sorbonne for a one-year course called \'93
Civilisation Francaise\'94, which was geared for foreigners. It was actually the Baccalaureate, and my mother was very positive, and in those days, it was I think it was only \'a320 a term fees, and you went to a hostel, and my grandmother \endash 
 my father\rquote s mother, who my mother always hated \endash  she left my mother some gas shares, that\rquote s before they discovered North Sea Gas, my mother said, \'93I\rquote m selling my gas shares so you can go to France\'94
. But actually, that was before my grandmother died, that\rquote s right, my grandmother wrote a seve
re letter saying that it was very dangerous to send me to Paris, and that I would be raped or that kind of thing. So I went to the Sorbonne for a year, and this was my freedom. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
