\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Yes. And having failed French \lquote A\rquote 
 Level, that despite this wonderful woman encouraging me, the teaching was so bad, I failed my French \lquote A\rquote  Level. I went to the Sorbonne, I could read and read and read. I didn\rquote 
t need to read with a torch under the bedclothes! I wandered free through all the streets \endash  I\rquote ve written about this in my de Beauvoir book \endash 
 and I was just blotting paper. We had the most brilliant lecturers, they were superstars, who then taught a bit to the foreigners. I came back in about Easter, for a holiday, and I said, \'93Mum, I\rquote m going to Oxford\'94. And she said, \'93
Get that out of your head. I can never afford to send you to Oxford\'94. Of course, this is what galls me now with the fees. Fortunately, my mo
ther sent away to the Local Authority to ask if they could contribute some money towards the Sorbonne, and a brilliant civil servant sent her a leaflet saying, \'93We don\rquote 
t finance overseas universities, but it depends on your salary, whether you can go to an English university\'94. And on the form it showed my mother\rquote 
s salary was sufficiently low for her to be able to have a full grant for me. So I felt under no guilt. I said, \'93Mum, you don\rquote t have to pay a bean! Your salary as a social worker \'85\'94 \endash  because she was still a social worker \endash  
\'93\'85 is so low, I\rquote m going to Oxford\'94. And despite the Headmistress, I went to this lovely Mr. Skidelski, who geared me for how to take exams, and at the interview, I was told, \'93You\rquote ve read more French literature than you\rquote 
ll have time to read in the whole of your three years!\'94 (LAUGHS) }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
