\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Well, it\rquote s funny, because my mother showed me a school report by the Headmaster \endash  God knows where it is now, if I
\rquote ve thrown it away \endash  but it actually said, \'93Judith is brilliant\'94. And I was eight then. But what was interesting was that both my sister and I, like children do, we picked up a Lincolnshire accent. We \lquote d say, \'93grass\'94
, and we\rquote d say, \'93water\'94, and my father and mother would tease us, but children are bilingual, they do that. I was taught to write with amazing looped handwriting, and when I went to the boarding school, they said, \'93That\rquote 
s how maids write\'94. And so I had to go back, at the age of nine, to writing with unjoined up letters and no loops, in order to re-learn that I shouldn\rquote t have a working-class writing, and no trace of a Lincolnshire accent. Again, I\rquote 
ve got another article. Huddersfield University have a Centre for British Identity, and suddenly, by chance, on group e-mails about anthropology of Britain, they said, \'93There\rquote s a conference on the other British Isles\'94
. So I sent an abstract, 18 months ago, on the Isle of Wight, and I said it was a place of prison, that it was where you imprisoned the upper classes, but also the most dangerous prisoners were put in Parkhurst. So I said, \'93There\rquote 
s this other island that has this paradox of being close to the upper classes with the Cowes sailing. Even the Head of BP went on a sailing Cowes thing, when he escaped Florida, and that was considered a scandal. So it\rquote 
s got all these paradoxes, and I said that I\rquote ve been obsessed with prisons ever since, because I was actually imprisoned there for nine years. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
