\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 The Upper Chine, because it was named after an amazing little stream with hu
ge banks. Ironically, I went, with a friend, in 1998, he was External Examiner at Southampton, and he said, \'93Oh, let\rquote s do a day trip to Isle of Wight\'94, because he was the son of a railwayman, and he said, \'93
We always had free travel, and we would go to the Isle of Wight as a holiday\'94, you know, working-class. It was a place for mass tourism as well as the upper classes and Queen Victoria and Alfred Tennyson, it\rquote 
s got all these paradoxes. We drove to my boarding school, and I started wandering around, and he said, \'93It\rquote s closed\'94. I said, \'93It can\rquote t be closed!\'94 He said, \'93Look, there\rquote s nobody here. It should be \lquote A\rquote 
 Level time\'94. And it was just being sold off. And I managed to get permission to return a month later with a professional film-maker, and with somebody I\rquote d meanwhile met at a conference, because she\rquote 
d read my boarding school article, and she revealed she\rquote d been to the School \endash  she recognised it from my article. And we filmed, we went all round. I\rquote ve got an article on that, and it was actually bulldozed an
d demolished a month later. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
