\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
Oh, it was. Mmm, yeah. The irony is that the international elite were sent there. We had a cousin of Queen Soraya of Iran. We had a number of children from Iran, from Singapore, from Canada, Africa, and after lights out, I h
ad a bed next to a woman called Mina Movaga, and she would teach me Persian. And that was my escape. She would tell me about the Caspian Sea and everything. Only three days ago I went into a newsagent in Oxford, behind that awful Bonn Square, and I heard 
these two guys talking, and I said, \'93What language?\'94 And they said, \'93Parsee\'94. So I said, \'93Yeck dor ser johapanshish\'94 (PHONETIC) \'93Doctor, a bad doctor\'94, and they went, \'93Oh!\'94 (LAUGHS) It\rquote 
s magic! So there were wonderful things in that I learnt, ironically, about other cultures. But there was a wonderful woman called Mimi Calvarti, who I\rquote 
ve since seen, she was short-listed for the T.S. Eliot poetry prize 18 months ago, two years ago, and they were talking about her work on the radio, and she\rquote s got a book of poe
try called The Chine. So I contacted her through her agent, and then I sent her my book with the two articles on the boarding school that are in here, and she said, \'93Judith! Oh, how did you remember that?! My God!\'94
 And she sent me a copy of her poetry. And this is the moving thing, is that she said she was awarded a Royal Mail Poetry Fellowship. She was sent to this school, aged five. She didn\rquote t go back to Iran until she was 18. And she said, \'93
As I was writing, thinking about what themes for this Royal Mail thing, I thought, \lquote Letters home\rquote , and then I thought, \lquote What\rquote s home?\rquote \'94
 And she thought her home is Upper Chine. So she went back to the School two years after I had filmed it, and it had all been bulldozed, and she was devastated. And all she could remember and see was the vegetation, because it\rquote 
s been turned into a sort of B & B and houses have been built. But then I had this historic meeting with her. I taped our interview, and I came with a shortened DVD of some of the footage. She was desperate, she said, \'93Judith, can I use this? You
\rquote ve got the Chapel! You\rquote ve got the gym!\'94 It was so poignant! So I\rquote m saying there are the memories, but I learnt, very early on, that I hated the place, and I think my sister didn\rquote t know she hated it. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 What did you hate about it? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
\par 
\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 I went there - I only discovered a year later, the day my father died. I was reading in The Times in the library, and there was \'93
In Memoriam\'94, which my father\rquote s parents had put, \'93October 9th\'94. I wasn\rquote t even told. So then I discovered that we were sent off to that school only ten days before he died. We weren\rquote 
t told till November. So I think I hated it that I was not allowed to grieve. The most important person in my life, who was teaching me French, who was taking me on wonderful bike rides, and we weren\rquote 
t allowed to show emotion. It was breaking the rules to cry. So I think, from then on, I became a rebel. I\rquote ve been to psychotherapy and all sorts, and one woman said \endash  I went to a therapist here who specialises on people who go to boardi
ng school \endash  and she said, interestingly, \'93Judith, no wonder you\rquote ve emphasised autobiography, because that\rquote s the only thing you had. You had to retreat into yourself\'94
. I would imagine that my father was still alive, and that one day he would be wheeled out in a wheelchair, and they were hiding him. I\rquote m saying it\rquote s retrospective, but I hated the rules. I wasn\rquote 
t sporty, whereas Mimi Calvarti, she said, \'93Judith, I was encouraged, because\'94 - and she came up with this dreaded word, \'93I was an all-rounder. I was go
od at hockey, I was good at netball, I was good at languages, I was good at this, and good at that.\'94
 We had compulsory sports every day, an hour and a half of compulsory hockey, and it was all orders, orders, orders, whistle, whistle. Then when I went back
 with this film-maker, we bumped into several other of our contemporaries, because they were busy clearing the Chapel. They were devoted. They knew the School was going to be dismantled, and they were trying to find the owners \endash  the donors \endash 
 of these Chapel chairs. And I took a chair, I took one for my sister and one for myself, and I\rquote ve got one in my study. The one thing we all said was, \'93Do you remember Miss Passmore?\'94 Called her \'93Pig\'94
. And she would come up behind you, and she\rquote d put her finger, like a bayonet, into the back, saying, \'93Stand up straight. Stand up straight\'94. The emphasis was on sports, and I was an intellectual. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Mmm, posture and that, I suppose. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
