\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Well, you couldn\rquote t talk in the passage, you couldn\rquote 
t talk after lights out. When could you talk? You had break time at eleven - the bell, the electric bell would go every 20 minutes. When the bell, electric bell, rang in th
e morning, and you were lying in bed, you had to be standing by the time the bell stopped, which was maybe three minutes. So it was all orders, orders, orders, discipline, discipline. This lovely woman I went with, Susan Caffrey - she was a lecturer in so
ciology at Greenwich University \endash  and we both realised how we became intellectuals, we said we didn\rquote 
t fit in, because her mother was divorced, and that was an absolute stigma, and her mother, in order to be near her daughter, her mother became the Housekeep
er at the School. And in the end, I think it was Susan, anyway, at least one of the children, they just stopped eating. In the end, Susan \endash  I think she stopped eating \endash  and the Headmistress said, \'93You\rquote re daughter\rquote 
s got to leave, because she\rquote s going to die\'94. We didn\rquote t fit into the nuclear family, and both of our mothers were downwardly mobile, and so we thought we were critical. And she became a sociologist. She also said, she said, \'93They couldn
\rquote t handle crises\'94. I\rquote ve written in this article on the Isle of Wight, that one of the girls went mad. Her parents were in Kenya \endash  and this was the height of the Mau Mau \endash 
 and she saw them maybe once a year for maybe a month, but she had grandparents in Sandown, next to Shanklin \endash  the School was at Shanklin. It was wond
erful, because a girl would be allowed to take out another girl to go out with visiting relatives, and these lovely older grandparents in Sandown, we\rquote d spend the Saturday afternoon with them, and then go back to the School. Suddenly Jenny\rquote 
s grandfather died \endash  and again, no account was taken for mourning \endash 
 and Jenny would lie in bed, weeping, howling, and I would break all the rules and go by her bedside, and try and comfort her. In the end, she became totally distracted, and I think she got \lquote flu and she was
 in the Sick Room, and she became mad. She kept saying there were little men coming through the windows, also black men, and they were falling down the walls. She was going mad. And we had a rota where we secretly went and said, \'93Could we see Jenny?
\'94 They didn\rquote 
t understand it! Then there was a day out where we went, once a year, to the cinema, and she was at the cinema, and she started going down the aisle, acting like a dog, lifting her leg, pretending she was peeing on all the seats. And she was sent to a
 mental hospital, and I never know what\rquote s happened to her since. So they couldn\rquote 
t even understand madness. And yet they thought they were caring for us. I broke my arm, they told me I was trying to get attention. For two weeks I had it in a sling, and then the Matron said to me, \'93You\rquote ve got to stop trying, you\rquote 
re just trying to get attention because your Daddy\rquote s died\'94 and, \'93Take this scarf off\'94. Then she turned me round, and she said, \'93Okay, darling. You can wear that sling\'94. I didn\rquote t understand what was ha
ppening. The next day, we were marching out \endash  because we had to march to military music \endash 
 she stood in the corridor, and she went like this - this is the Matron - and then she took me up to the local cottage hospital for an X-ray. And it was broken here. She just said to the X-ray woman, \'93
Yes, well, I turned her round, and her left shoulder was hanging lower than her right\'94. So my mother thought we were being cared for. My sister broke her foot. It was never - she\rquote s still got a permanent bump. It was a brutal regime. I don
\rquote t care when people say, \'93Look, after the War, you needed to pretend that everything was normal\'94. I\rquote m sorry, it\rquote s left its wounds. It might be explained by the War, but that\rquote 
s not the way you deal with it. Like I said, the Queen didn\rquote t unde
rstand, ironically, that the nation was mourning Princess Diana, and that her boys this, that, and the other, and it just completely unleashed - it broke the stiff upper lip British culture. Actually, most of those people were crying for other deaths. It 
was vicarious mourning. They weren\rquote t really mourning for Princess Diana, who, again, she didn\rquote t even have an \lquote O\rquote  Level. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 But were there no positively significant teachers at the School? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
