\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Well, it\rquote s that I came out with a very very bad degree, which I think was total injustice. When I had the viva, I\rquote 
m very proud of what I said in the viva, and this dreadful 
man, Pilchinski, he sniggered through my answers. I realise, retrospectively, I was actually doing a Paul Willis Learning to Labour, before that book had been written, but I was sent away, and my career was ruined, because I wanted to be an academic. But 
my then boyfriend, in my last year, was this man called Hugh Brody, and he got a fairly mediocre PPE Degree as well, but he was marked as \'93gifted\'94, and they gave him \endash  that was when the SSRC was just starting \endash 
 so they gave him an SSRC grant, and he decided to look at the theme of demoralisation in the West of Ireland. But we had one year living in Upper Heyford, in Oxford \endash 
 and this is where I - starting, that I began to move beyond my social class, including meeting Mr. Busby. Hugh had a wonderful way of getting to know people beyond his class, and I\rquote m sure it\rquote 
s something to do with him being an outsider. He was Jewish, one side of his ancestors were Austrian and disappeared in the camps and whatever, and then I went, with him, to the West of Ireland, as his wife \endash  with a Belfast Woolworths wedding ring 
\endash  and I learnt about fieldwork. I was just doing part-time teaching at the College of FE at Banbury Tech. and whatever, and then I did a Certificate in Education at Garnett College, and then we broke up. Then
 I learnt about other cultures. This was the time of the Swinging Sixties, and yet we were going to the West of Ireland, living with the most amazing people who just lived off potatoes and an egg a day or something, and when I did my anthropology course, 
Leach had a whole course on Malinowski \endash  there were only five of us, because they didn\rquote t have a proper post-grad thing, it was all undergrads, but there were just five of us doing a Conversion Course \endash  and I thought, \'93
I know about fieldwork\'94. I also had learnt, instinctively, that your gender and your ethnicity - because Hugh was Jewish, called \'93Brody\'94, but they all relabelled him \'93Brady\'94
, they thought he must have Irish ancestry, he never revealed that. His supervisor, Brian Wilson, absolutely bonkers, told him, \'93You mustn\rquote t go with anybody else\'94, because he knew we lived together. \'93You\rquote 
ve got to be a bachelor, and you\rquote ve got to say you\rquote re Catholic\'94. Well, how can you say somebody who has been brought up as an Orthodox Jew, to pretend to be Catholic and go to Confession? It\rquote 
s absolutely bonkers. So I had that sort of scepticism. You can\rquote t pretend to be Catholic if you\rquote re Jewish, and then go through the parade of going to Confession! You\rquote 
d be found out as a fraud! So there were all these things. And the final twist was, I\rquote d left Hugh, ... he wrote up this book, Inishkillane, and I didn\rquote 
t feature in at all. So this is the thing about what is actually going on in the field? I went there with my Belfast wedding ring, in a Catholic community. You couldn\rquote t say, \'93Look, you know, we\rquote re living together. We\rquote 
ve been together for two years\'94, and \'93Can we have a double room?\'94 sort of thing. We were greeted, and they would say, \'93When did you get married?\'94 and all that sort of thing. We had to invent a date and all that, and what shocked me \endash 
 I think this must have been the trigger \endash  was to read this book. He came and gave me a copy, we met up in a pub in London. I was, by then, employed on the Gypsy Project at Regent\rquote s Park, and he put the book down on the table, and he said, 
\'93You\rquote re going to be very angry when you read this\'94. I was just fascinated \endash  and I\rquote ve written it all up in this article \endash  that I didn\rquote t feature! And it actually starts in the first person, \'93
When I arrived at Kate Neagh\rquote s place.\'94 Because we got to know Kate Neagh, because another person in Lower Heyford, Maud Kennedy, an artist, she painted this [picture] of Mr. Busby, Maud told us to meet Kate Neagh, because Maud had lived \endash 
 and that\rquote s some of her paintings up there. Maud, brilliant, brilliant artist \endash  she t
old us to contact Kate Neagh because Maud had during the War, disappeared to the West of Ireland, with her children, to escape bombing or whatever. She, herself, wasn\rquote 
t Catholic or Irish, and Kate was her neighbour. So when we turned up at that place, we just said, \'93Look, we\rquote re friends of Maud\'94. And Kate said, \'93Oh, me darlings!\'94 you know! And Hugh\rquote s book starts out with, \'93
Oh, me darlings! And then we had tea.\'94 So I was written out! }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
