\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Well, it put me on to thinking all these monographs I\rquote d been reading, how did they do it? There\rquote s no descri
ption of the fieldwork. Of course, Clifford and Marcus have the famous arrival scenes, they\rquote re very clever in their book, Riding Culture. They say that anthropologists said, \'93We\rquote re true scientists. We\rquote re not literary people. We
\rquote re not travelogues\'94. I think it was Mary Louise Pratt said, \'93They\rquote ve used the literary trope, which is the arrival scene, and that is straight out of literature\'94
. So I began to look, unpick the texts, and I was frustrated in that course because there was nothing about how you did fieldwork, or how people did fieldwork. That was when Malinowski\rquote s diary was published \endash  in \rquote 
67 it had been published \endash  and I was fascinated, and Leach said, \'93It should never have been published\'94. And I since wrote an article on it. I actually wrote it before Gertz or anybody else. Of course, because it was in Jasso (?? \endash 
 121.06), it didn\rquote t get the same publicity. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
