\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 The Self and Scientism. Yes, yes, I reprinted it, yes. But it was considered, you know, it\rquote s now co
nsidered pioneering. But Gertz, you know, everybody was arguing, but I\rquote m saying that I think it was, because even in the seventies, when I was writing up my Ph.D., I started writing drafts of this of this article. Yeah, I started writing, like, 
\'93How could he say that this guy was trying to commit suicide?\'94 or something, and I\rquote ve argued that I have a different take on it. But Hugh\rquote s interpretation I didn\rquote 
t agree with. And also, the key thing was that his whole thing was that the West of Ireland was decaying 
and demoralised, and I saw stamina, ingenuity, persistence. I admired these people. And women were invisible in his text! So I began to look at gender and what was the construction of a monograph? Because I knew that there was a monograph that was fake. I
 mean, not all fake, but he\rquote d written me out. And he\rquote d been praised for being this lone man who\rquote d broken through the jungle of the boom docks of West of Ireland, and actually gone and talked to peasants! }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
