\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
Yes! Yeah, well, that was the wonderful thing. Because dear Paul Barker, he would send me all these anthropology books to review for New Society. He was utterly amazing. I mean, it\rquote 
s such a tragedy that that journal stopped. And I was asked to review a book by Pocock, and there was the notion of a personal anthropology. But before that, you had to have a sort of patent. You had to have a rationale, because when I proposed this with 
Helen, it was a huge uproar. I was in Essex at the time, and I\rquote d come back from my trips in Normandy. I\rquote 
d been in France, I was English, it was very specific. They loved the fact that I was Anglaise in Normandy, because the English had helped with the Norma
ndy Landings, so I was feted wherever I went! The Mayor lifted up the wine and drank to this Anglaise! (LAUGHS) I was swept off! So I suddenly thought, \'93God, you know, my identity as Anglaise facilitated everything!\'94
 So I came back, and I suddenly thought, there\rquote s an ASA, and you have to put a proposal two years in advance, and I rang up the Director, and they said, \'93You have to have a hundred copies of your proposal on the very first day in\'94
 - was it in Ipswich? Yes, was it Ipswich or no, it was Norwich. Norwich. And I, literally, rang around friends, saying, \'93Would you do a joint proposal with me?\'94 One friend wasn\rquote 
t in, and I rang up this wonderful Helen Callaway, and she was all into literary theory, and she said, \'93Okay\'94. I scribbled the proposal, I took it into lovely Carol, the typist in Essex, that morning \endash  because I couldn\rquote 
t type in those days \endash  and she typed it, and I took 100 photocopies, and I took the train to Norwich \endash  I had to be there by two \endash  and I proposed it. But Tim Ingold, he had thought his proposal was all wrapped up, and he\rquote 
d gathered two other rivals so they could do a huge thing on \'93Man and Nature\'94 I think it was, and he hadn\rquote t even bothered to turn up! Marilyn Strathern was delegated, because she was professor at Manchester, to do the
 proposal. So you had to stand up in a huge conference meeting at the end of the week, and speak for your proposal, and then there\rquote d be a vote, open, hands up \endash 
 you know, there was 200 people there! Marilyn had to speak for Tim Ingold. Before I\rquote d spoken, the rumblings were, \'93This is a Feminist plot. It\rquote s Narcissism\'94
, and Tony Cohen, who was later to be my colleague in Edinburgh, he shouted out, \'93California-speak! There are loads and loads of Narcissistic books, navel-gazing crap. We don\rquote t want another one like that\'94. Anyway, I\rquote 
m very proud of myself, because I was so nervous, I was absolutely hyperventilating, and I actually went to the corridor - the loo wasn\rquote t there, and I took my top off, and then my vest! And if anybody had seen me, I was half naked! (LA
UGHS) Anyway, the vote came, and the dinosaurs \endash  Leach and Raymond Firth, and Edmund \endash  they all put their hands up for me! And we had an overwhelming vote! But it was considered \'93California-speak Narcissism\'94
. And it was actually a brilliant conference. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
