\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Well, I was invited to give the Phyllis Karberry Lecture, in 1989, which was part of the Gender Centre. Every year there\rquote 
s a lecture, commemorative, in honour of different anthropologists, and I decided to celebrate individuals who didn\rquote t fit in. It\rquote s called \'93Defiant Moments\'94. And I devoted half the lecture to Madame Gregoire \endash 
 the Frenchwoman who taught me how to hand milk cows, and really changed the direction of my research \endash  and Mr. Busby, absolutely wonderful man! Hugh and I met him through Maud [Kennedy], the painter. He lived round the corner \endash 
 there he is as a young man, I got all these photos \endash  he was a deserter from the First World War, and this was amazing, because in those days, as he said, the Conscientious Objectors were middle-class \'85 He was a lad who\rquote 
d left school at 12 or something, and he knew that you couldn\rquote t say, \'93I\rquote m not going to fight\'94 for the First World War, but he didn\rquote t agree with it, but he said, \'93You had to enlist, because you bring shame on the village\'94
. He lived in a village north of [Oxford], he lived in Kiddington at the time. In the end, he said, \'93I was a Communist and an atheist\'94. Anyway, it\rquote s all there. We would go and sit at his feet and listen to his storie
s. Then when Hugh and I broke up, I lost contact \endash  I always called him \'93Mr. Busby\'94 \endash  but when I got my post-grad. grant, I\rquote 
d done my main research, but I got one at Oxford, I just drove off like a homing pigeon, back to Lower Heyford where he had a bungalow. I hadn\rquote t seen him for about five or six years, and I just came through the door and I said, \'93
Hello, do you know who I am?\'94 He said, \'93It\rquote s my Judith!\'94 And then I tape-recorded him \endash  his stories. I\rquote ve been in touch with Ian Hislop because he did stories of First World War deserters and Conscientious Objectors. He
\rquote s unique, because this is a working-class lad. And he escaped, he got a ticket to go to, he thought, to Guyana. But anyway, it\rquote s all in the story. And he wrote a poem about it, and he dictated it to me. So I thought, \'93
I will, in Oxford, in the Taylorian Institute, I will reinstate you\'94, like your community studies, \'93I will put, in profile, a brilliant hero who lived only 15 miles from there\'94. And, in fact, a very upper class anthropologist came up 
to me after, and said, \'93Oh Judith, how did you ever meet him?\'94 (LAUGHS) And somebody else said to me, \'93How could you not have met him if you lived in that village!\'94 But this upper class guy, who\rquote 
s done work in an exotic part of the world, he wouldn\rquote t dream of talking to the villagers! And Maud really captured him in that beautiful picture. So he was an inspiration to me. I taped him reminiscing, and I\rquote 
m going to give the cassettes to the Imperial War Museum \endash  I must, soon, before the house is burnt or whatever, and the cassettes destroyed. So there\rquote s an example of oral history. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
