\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Well, I started doing French and Latin. And, of course, the other thing is, I realised that I\rquote 
ve struggled all the way, because they said they would accept me for the French, but because I\rquote d been taught Latin so badly at my school, that they said, informally, on the phone, they offered me a place to Oxford, but they said if I\rquote 
m only doing one modern language, one language, I had to do Latin up to Prelims.. But they said I would have \endash  informally, not in writing \endash  that I would have to do a test in Latin before going up to St. Hilda\rquote 
s. So between being given a place in January, I then did a Wolsley Correspondence Course in Latin, and then they said they\rquote d give me a test, and I was so honest \endash 
 Margaret, who was fluent in Latin, they sent the test in about June/July, and Margaret, on my mother\rquote s kitchen table, invigilated and timed it, and then we posted
 it off. I mean, we could have cheated! And then Margaret and I went off hitch-hiking, we went to Spain and goodness knows, and when I came back in about September, whatever, my mother greeted me with the message that there was a letter from St. Hilda
\rquote s saying that they\rquote d rejected my place because I\rquote d failed the Latin. And again, she said, \'93You\rquote ve got to be a secretary\'94. I\rquote m saying, \'93I am a rebel. I don\rquote t take no\'94. I found the letter from St. Hilda
\rquote s, it said, \'93We are pleased to award you a place to read Modern Languages\'94. I rang up Mrs. Gerard-Davies at St. Hilda\rquote s, and I said, \'93You\rquote ve turned me down\'94, and I said, \'93It\rquote 
s too late for me to apply to any other university, and you tell me this in September\'94. She said, \'93Well, we\rquote ve given your place to somebody else now. It\rquote s too late, anyway\'94. And I said, \'93But the letter says I\rquote 
ve been given a place. It doesn\rquote t say, \lquote provided you pass the Latin\rquote \'94. So I was an internal lawyer. And even my mother hadn\rquote t seen through that. She said, \'93Will you promise you\rquote ll be good at Latin?\'94 and I said, 
\'93I promise\'94. She rang me back an hour later, and she said, \'93We\rquote ll find you a place\'94. But I could have lost it. But as Margaret said, she said, \'93I could\rquote 
ve written that test for you. We could have cheated. Or you could have spent six hours over it!\'94 Anyway, so when I come back up, the Latin is a nightmare, because you\rquote 
re not allowed just to do French, but you had to do Latin up to Prelims., and the fear was that I was going to fail Latin again. I failed it at Prelims. Meanwhile I was g
etting a reputation of somebody on the Left, and I was active in the Labour Club. One guy said, \'93Oh, we\rquote ve got to\'94 - he was on the Left, and he said, \'93Oh, Gerry\'94
, there was a guy who taught Classics at Exeter or Wadham, called Gerry [Fowler], he later became an MP, and apparently the male students went to him and said, \'93There\rquote s a good woman on the Left, would you prepare her for Latin?\'94
 And so he gave me tutorials in Latin, and I had to sit it again. And I remember, I got totally drunk on cider, and I went to the Schools to re-take the Latin, thinking, \'93I\rquote m finished\'94, and I actually passed it! }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
