\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 I was already incipient critique, because I said I got up in the Civics class and complained about the Suez thing, and I also complain
ed about Cyprus. My mother\rquote s cousin was Acting Governor of Cyprus as it happened! (LAUGHS) I became atheist/agnostic \endash 
 again, it was an anthropological moment, because I would go, every week, originally with those two English girls, to the Anglican church 
in the centre of Paris, the elite faubourg something or other, and I went in, and I was ready to take Communion after the ordinary mass and everything, and it was a St. Paul\rquote 
s moment on the road to Damascus, because there was this English clergyman talking probably about warm beer and cricket, like John Major, and I thought, \'93We\rquote re in the middle of Paris, and we\rquote 
re talking as if this little island is in England, and we\rquote re talking about cricket and class. What am I doing?\'94 I said to my English friend, \'93I literally, I\rquote ve come in to take Communion\'94, and I said, \'93I\rquote 
m not staying for Communion\'94. I was still a Christian, and I walked out of that church, and then I bought a Bible in French, because I still believed in the King James Bible. And gradually, it was just another story. So that was it. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
