\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 No, because I had never really learnt to speak, you know. And funny enough, the John Thane, the then husband of Pat Thane \endash 
 you know her? She\rquote s a historian. We met up, because she asked me to help launch that book last March. After the first vote, John Thane and an Indian guy, they both spoke against women joining the Union, because they said, \'93There\rquote 
s some women who are \'94 - because I got huge media attention, even before the vote, because I had my long hair and my leather jacket and my contemporaries all had short cropped hair and I was a hippy/Bohemian. John Thane said, \'93
Some people are exploiting it just to get their name in the media\'94, and I knew I wasn\rquote t going to stand for office unless I was a good speaker, and I was totally inexperienced, so I didn\rquote 
t. I never stood as a speaker, or for office. It was a symbolic gesture, that was all. I spoke once in a follow-up debate, but I wasn\rquote t interested in high office. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
