\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
I know! (LAUGHS) Nobody in French. Then I said I switched to PPE. We had Miss Crowe, who was Right-wing. The lectures by Alasdair McIntyre, the phil
osopher, and Lord Hart, who gave some sensational lectures on the absurdity of sexual regulations in American law - because the other thing was, the lectures were nothing to do with the syllabus \endash  that\rquote 
s the Oxford system! You know, it was somebody giving lectures on their forthcoming book. But Alasdair McIntyre was great, and Lord Hart, A.L. Hart. I once told a woman reader up in African Studies, or Law, or something, in Edinburgh, and she said, \'93
My God, you went to his lectures! Oh!\'94 So those two were fascinating. And then I was lucky because Gareth, he\rquote 
d graduated the year before me, with a stunning First, and he got a place in Nuffield, and he knew Stephen Lukes. This was the first year they introduced sociological theory. You had two options, it was the
 first year they introduced sociology, and also political theory you could choose, so Gareth asked Stephen if he would be willing to supervise me to do the course, one-to-one. I did political theory, that was it, with him, and I did sociological theory wi
th Brian Wilson \endash  the one who later became Hugh\rquote s supervisor. And it was quite funny because Stephen rang me up about two years ago (LAUGHS), he said, \'93This is Stephen Lukes\'94. I said, \'93No! Stephen!\'94 He\rquote 
d got my phone number, he was at a conference in Budapest, and he wanted me to review a book on gypsies. We reminisced, and then I said, \'93Do you know, Stephen, I thanked you in the preface to my gypsy book\'94. I said, \'93You threw me a landline\'94
. Because at the end of my essay on Marx, he sat there, and he said, \'93That is the best essay I\rquote ve ever heard on Marx\'94, so I\rquote d read the stuff. And I jokingly said it to him on the phone two years ago, and he said, \'93I can\rquote 
t remember that!\'94 (LAUGHS) }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 I remember, it was in the book! (LAUGHS) }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
\par 
\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 (LAUGHS) But Stephen gave me hope. And then I wanted to go on and do an MA in Sociology at the LSE, and I had to get references 
\endash  that was before the Finals \endash  and Miss Crowe rang up Stephen Lukes and said, \'93You are apparently putting your name down as a referee for Judith Okely. What on earth are you doing with that?\'94 And he said, \'93She\rquote 
s brilliant! She\rquote s going to get a First\'94. And Miss Crowe said, \'93No, she\rquote s going to get a Third\'94. (LAUGHS) And she was right! }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Oh yes, of course! }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 

\par 
\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 But just to carry on about this,
 that was the only person that gave me any hope. Because that was the other thing, you had women tutors who were often very bitter and angry. They all said they lost fianc\'e9s in the War, just like the women at my boarding school, and they weren\rquote 
t adventurous. And I said, \'93Miss Crowe made me [for] three successive tutorials, write essays on administrative law\'94, and I was talking to my male colleagues and they said, \'93It\rquote s not even on the syllabus\'94. They weren\rquote 
t on the Examination Boards. When I later emerged, 
having done that research job at the Centre for Environmental Studies, and then I registered for a D.Phil., at my own expense originally, until I was lucky to get an ESRC grant, I was talking to somebody, at some event \endash  he was at Nuffield \endash 
 and I met up with him later, and he said, \'93Judith, the mention of your name to Miss Crowe, has shortened her life by five years at least. She couldn\rquote t stop going on, \lquote 
What a disgrace to the University that that woman is registered for a D.Phil., and she wasted her time in the Union and in the Labour Club\rquote \'94
. And I went to a party that Stephen was giving then, and I was in tears, and I told him that, and he said, \'93Judith, she\rquote s a disgrace to the University\'94. So, we talk about mentoring, where is the mentoring? No. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 No. So you had to find your own way. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
