\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Well, I said I was devastated when I got the Third, you see. You had to go to the School\rquote 
s building, and you looked at the list, and I was behind a queue of people, and I couldn\rquote t see myself First or Second, and I remember going to the Parks and just lyin
g on the grass and weeping, weeping. Anyway, I was with Hugh at the time, so he got the grant, but we both went off to Greece, by the way, on holiday. It was then his brother, who was married to a Greek woman, suddenly got a phone call saying, \'93
Tell Hugh Brody to come back to Oxford\'94. Those were the days where - it was the founding of the [SSRC] Michael Young started that, didn\rquote t he? And he was given, he scraped a 2:1, well, a Second, but he was a \'93Golden Boy\'94
. And that makes me angry, because at Trinity, where he was, they had special tutorials to give them mock questions, in the last term, and it turned out to be so good that lots of men from other Colleges would go. But us women couldn\rquote 
t go because they\rquote d know we weren\rquote t members of Trinity. So they were rehearsed. They were told what questions were going to come up, and \'93 These are the best answers!\'94
 Anyway, so [Hugh] got an award, and then we went to live in this cottage in Upper Heyford. He would go to lectures in Oxford, and I was just the lowest of the low, and I got \endash 
 and this is actually crucial for research purposes, this was another learning thing \endash  I can\rquote t remember which came first, but I had two part-time jobs, one was working with Henri Tajfel, the famous psychologist. It\rquote 
s funny, there was a whole radio programme on him, talking about \'93group mentality\'94, he\rquote 
d done some research on that, and again, there they were praising him and blah, blah, on the radio. My interview consisted of me going to Wellington Square, to his room, and him touching me up all the way through the interview \endash 
 running his hand up and down my arm, trying to grab my breast. I mean, you know, the audacity of it! And I couldn\rquote t protest because I wanted the job! And it was to interview primary school children about their attitudes 
to race. And I told Hugh afterwards that I\rquote d been touched up by this guy, and Hugh was livid, and he told Stephen Lukes, who then said, ... \'93You just have to get used to it\'94
. So, you know, there was Feminism of a sort, but nobody had looked at sexual explo
itation or power/abuse. Anyway, I never saw the man again, Tajfel, because I was doing work for Nick Somebody. So you sat in a primary school in Headington, and there was a little board, with \'93Like very much\'94 and \'93Don\rquote t like\'94
, and you read a story to a primary school kid, and in some cases they named the nationality, I think a German or an English kid, a hero or heroine. It was quite clever because he was testing whether they didn\rquote 
t like the hero because they were labelled \'93German\'94. But I never saw the resu
lts. And this guy Nick, who I was working for, he then wrote an article in New Society, and I was trying to look it up the other day, but again, this was the shock, that he met me in a very embarrassed way, because he said, \'93Oh, I\rquote 
m sorry, I didn\rquote t mention you in the article\'94
. I did most of the research, and he published it under his name. So that was an insight into power abuse into research. And then the next one was most helpful. I learnt so much. There was a guy at Nuffield \endash  again it was a part-time jo
b, two or three days a week \endash  and he had loads of money to look at a Shopping Centre in Cowley. And there\rquote s the famous Shopping Centre, which name I always forget because it\rquote s got a sort of mediaeval name, but there\rquote 
s one in Between Towns Road. But there were all these business people wanting to find out whether it was worth building a Shopping Centre. So he had all this money to do his Ph.D., and he recruited me and the American wife of an academic, as usual 
\endash  there were lots of intelligent women around who didn\rquote t have jobs. She and I were both recruited to conduct questionnaire surveys around Cowley. It was terribly informative to me, because (a) I didn\rquote t know Cowley \endash 
 it was white working-class, Morris Motors and Cowley Motors then, it was full employment. And you had to go to every third house, and you had this questionnaire of about three or four pages, and it was all about shopping habits, and you had \'93Yes\'94, 
\'93No\'94, \'93Don\rquote t know\'94 \endash  they were pre-ordained answers. And then there was, right at the end, there was two inches, \'93Any other comments\'94
. And that was one of the most important lessons for me later, to learn about the limitations of questionnaire, because you would knock on the door and there would be an elderly woman who was desperate for company, and \'93Come in and have a cup of tea
\'94. And then you\rquote d say, \'93Do you buy your Sunday joint on a Friday or a Saturday?\'94 And she\rquote d say, \'93Look at me. I live alone. Do you think I\rquote 
m going to have a Sunday joint? Do you think I can even afford it? I go to the butchers when it\rquote s closing, and I might get a chop at a discount\'94. There wasn\rquote 
t room for those answers. And then I would keep filling up the later paragraph, you see. So that was the most useful practical lesson in scepticism, with pre-ordained questions. Then, every other day, we\rquote 
d have to report to this guy in Nuffield, and he\rquote d ask us what we\rquote d done and everything. I later discovered, through reading articles elsewhere, that often, when they gave the work to men, they would sit in caf\'e9s and they would forge the 
answers, so they could never understand why these patterns of voting didn\rquote t seem to fit. It\rquote s like the famous one with Truman, wasn\rquote t it, where they did a telephone call and, of course, half the population didn\rquote 
t have phones, so they thought Truman was going to win the election, and all he was doing was checking up that we\rquote d done it. This American, she was a graduate, and we both said how utterly dumb the questions were. So that was bloody useful. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
