\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Oh. No, it wasn\rquote t Geoff Dench, because he and I got on quite well, we\rquote 
d meet on the circuit. But there was one called The Asymmetrical Family and it was being done at the Centre for Environmental Studies, and what made me \endash  and I think it\rquote s in that article I\rquote ve referred to \endash 
 but, as it were, there\rquote s the lumpen proletariat who walk the street getting the information, and then the people write it up. And in The Symmetrical Family\endash 
 which Ann Oakley critiqued brilliantly, because they said that men now have equal roles in housework and all that \endash  and there was a whole page where they actually listed all the people who did the questionnaires, and I said, \'93
Well, at least they did mention the names, but that we were - what was it? Cash croppers?\'94 I remember a wonderful American woman at a conference, years later, saying, \'93French anth
ropologists who do work in Europe, treat researchers like cash croppers \endash  that you provide the material which then they write up\'94
. And anyway, all that influenced me to realise that the questionnaire was crap. But I think, again, there was this subterranea
n enthusiasm of my mother. I read Education and the Working Class, by the way, when I graduated, when I was sitting in Upper Heyford, and I was speechless when I came to Essex and there was Dennis Marsden! I just couldn\rquote 
t believe it, that there was a mentor, because that book was brilliant. And I\rquote ve always said, by the way, that the strength of that book was actually it drew on autobiography, because they\rquote 
d both been working-class grammar school boys made good, and they drew on their autobiography, almost unknowingly, to make sense of the material. I didn\rquote t realise fully that at the time. So I\rquote 
m saying that those are my two jobs. And then the third term, I got a job teaching, again once or twice a week \endash  how I found it \endash  in a secondary modern in Banbury, a Catholic secondary modern, twice a week, it\rquote 
s just laughable! I was the only graduate, they\rquote d all done teachers\rquote  training, and they were all heavy Catholics, and Mr. Grims, it\rquote s not Mr. Gradgrind, but it sounded like Mr. Gumption, or something like that, he
 was Headmaster, and he\rquote d done a correspondence degree from Africa, by correspondence, and he was Headmaster \endash  Mr. Grimshaw \endash  and he said, \'93You come to my class, and I\rquote ll teach you how to teach, and then you\rquote 
ll know how to teach, because you\rquote ve never taught before\'94. There was a book with, you know, \'93Bread is brown. Bread is white. Bread is something\'94, and they had to choose the right word, and they\rquote d put up their hands, and he\rquote 
d say, \'93Who said \lquote bread is brown?\rquote \'94 And the hands went up. \'93That\rquote s wrong, because it\rquote s also white! So that\rquote s a wrong answer!\'94 And then he said, \'93Who said that bread is spongy?\'94 \endash 
 because there was this choice of words \endash  \'93Bread isn\rquote t spongy, because that\rquote s a different - bread isn\rquote t sponge\'94, so no hands. And then he said, \'93There\rquote s only one thing that bread is, and that is wholesome!\'94
