e he decided that he was giving up his job and he was moving back to Oxford. I got a job teaching Further Education day-release at Banbury Tech. ... [After we broke up] I came back to Oxford, and was totally devastated, and by absolute chance, about three
 weeks before, some people had come to visit me in our cottage, some of them were from Ireland, and they\rquote 
d got word that Hugh was with this person, and they came as a sort of consolation delegation, not knowing whether I knew, but they liked me. Somebody gave a philosopher a lift, and this was this person, I didn\rquote t know who he was, I didn\rquote 
t even think he was English, he didn\rquote t say anything, he looked Polish to me, and anyway, the day I came back on the train, two days later, I bumped into this same guy in Ox
ford, and we went off for a cup of tea or something. We spent quite a lot of time together, and he was married with two children, and nothing happened, but this was somebody - I could just think about somebody else\'85
. [Then when Hugh wanted to reconcile] I held my ground. And this guy, I\rquote m afraid, enormous tragedy, left his wife and children, and I was with him for 17 years. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
