\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Yeah, well, he\rquote s able to worm his way in and get grants, but it\rquote s not a job that you get appointed to. I 
mean, the year that we broke up, he then - I said he wrote those books \endash  and then he went off to look at Native Americans in Canada. [There\rquote s] a terrific book, which one of my students has nicked \endash  it\rquote s a shame really \endash 
 but it\rquote s Life on Skid Row, and it was very very funny, because David Sibley, a geographer, he\rquote s written a book called, Urban Outsiders, and there\rquote 
s one whole chapter devoted to my work, and one whole chapter devoted to Hugh, because then Hugh went off to look at the Inuit. I said, \'93Isn\rquote t it funny that we both went to look at nomads\'94, and I said, \'93You didn\rquote 
t realise that we once lived together\'94. It was very very funny. But anyway, I got the taste, and so I thought, \'93Anthropology is me\'94. And my mother, again, she had books by Mead lying around, and the other twist is that when I was at St. Hilda
\rquote s, my mother said, \'93Margaret Mead is coming to give a lecture at London\'94 \endash  she was reading Growing up in New Guinea and Samoa, I\rquote ve still got her books \endash  and she said, \'93Well, you know, we could go to a lecture\'94
. And in those days, in Oxford, you had to get permission to leave Oxford overnight, and I think the lecture was on a Friday evening or a Saturday morning, and I went, in all decency, to the Principal, and asked if I could go to a lecture by Margare
t Mead, and she said, \'93No. You are in loco parentis\'94. I couldn\rquote t even go to a lecture by - and then the woman had the cheek to say, \'93If you were going to say farewell to your fianc\'e9
, who was flying to Australia, we would allow you the day off\'94. You know, a fictitious fianc\'e9! Well, I spoke at Warwick on Thursday \endash  I was invited to talk about Feminism \endash  and the students\rquote 
 mouths were opening when I was telling them \endash  \'93This is what we had to experience, as undergraduates\'94. Men were allowed to marry. It was just
 amazing! Jackie Lukes, who I got to know well, she said she was at Somerville, and she said the Principal called her and said there was one young woman, whose name I will not mention, who she was worried might get pregnant or something, and would Jackie 
look after her to make sure she didn\rquote t get pregnant! (LAUGHS) }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
