\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Stanley Tambiah. Absolutely brilliant! He\rquote s written Leach\rquote s biography. He is Sri Lankan. And he gave
 the most brilliant lectures, the beginning of the week it was on politics and economics, and at the end of the week it was on religion and ritual. To me, that was wonderful also, to somebody who had a Marxist perspective, that you could study religion an
d ritual and you could look at politics and economics, and they were ordered, they were beautifully presented. These young Czechs who arranged for me to have that, they\rquote ve interviewed me, and it\rquote 
s going to appear in a Czech journal, and they said, \'93You were taught by some of the most famous anthropologists. Can you tell us what they were like?\'94 And I said, \'93I\rquote m afraid dear old Meyer Fortes, he\rquote d say, \lquote 
Now, there are three main points\rquote  and he\rquote d never get to the second point!\'94 (LAUGHS) }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
