It is. And ironically, I was attached to Newnham, and you see, there again, you know, wherever I go, I seem to arouse hatred. I went, very very nervously, to the first - for new post-grads, there was an event at Newnham \endash 
 I was terribly nervous, I was coming, I\rquote d crept back to academia. I had to have a huge loan. I\rquote d worked my arse off. You know, I\rquote d economised, I hadn\rquote t bought clothes for two years \endash 
 nothing. And there were these new post-grads., and I\rquote ve since heard from my friend Susan \endash  the one who inherited Fortes\rquote s papers \endash  she said, \'93Judith, that woman was mad\'94 \endash  the Principal of Newnham. I didn\rquote 
t know at the time. And we all sat, after dinner, around on the floor, round her in her big room, and she said, \'93Any questions?\'94 I don\rquote t know what it was, I asked a perfectly genuine question, but there\rquote 
s something about my boarding school accent that arouses hatred, because people think I\rquote m privileged, and she just tore into me. I was devastated! And
 I went off to the Ladies later, and I just sobbed and sobbed, and there were two lovely Indian/Asian post-grads., and they said, they couldn\rquote t understand how that woman had treated me that way. I hadn\rquote 
t imagined it. They said it was just incomprehensible. I don\rquote 
t know what the question was, I asked. I was so upset, I left my handbag in the lodge, on the pavement, I cycled off back home. I had to ask one of the tenants if I could have a spare key to get in, and then I think I rang up Newnham, and they had m
y bag, a porter had my bag, but I never set foot in Newnham again. I just seem to arouse hatred. But anyway, they ring up, Onora O\rquote Neill, do you remember her at Essex? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
