\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 No. No. I didn\rquote t meet him. But anyway, Fortes said, \'93
You had a Third Class Degree, we can only give you an SSRC Grant if you get a Distinction in your exams\'94
. And again, it was exams only. And Malcolm marked one of my exams, and he said they were just absolutely outstanding. I did a re-analysis of the Cooler (?? \endash  sp. 61.46) but, of course, Leach didn\rquote 
t like it. There was no dissertation, you see. Now, with all these degrees, you have dissertations, it gives you a chance. I said Malcolm was wonderful, and he said, \'93Judith, you\rquote ve got to go on with anthropology\'94, and I said, \'93Yes, I have
\'94. And I knew I wouldn\rquote t get a Distinction, I just stressed out. I can\rquote t think quickly. Little did I know I had an underactive thyroid \endash  it wasn\rquote t discovered till I went to Hull years later, and the guy said, \'93
You were diagnosed with an underactive thyroid 20 years ago, and it says you refused to take the medicine\'94. I said, \'93Absolute rubbish!\'94 I said, \'93I could have written six more books!\'94
 (LAUGHS) Thank goodness the Hull guy, he read through my medical records. I said, \'93Well, it\rquote s the first time I knew that!\'94
 Anyway, just to end the story, is that I knew this was my subject - and this is where my mother comes in again. I was sitting in her study. She was a regular, she took New Society, and that was 1970, maybe August/September, and I said, \'93
Mum, this is my subject. I\rquote ve done French, I\rquote ve done literature, I\rquote ve done politics.\'94 I said, \'93This is me! I\rquote ve got to go on\'94
. And I was flipping through New Society, I mean, talk about serendipity and if you believe in God, there was an advert at the back, \'93Wanted, a researcher to look at gypsies and government policy. Centre for Environmental Studies, London\'94
. It was one of those QUANGOS that Heseltine later closed. And when I think of it, I hand wrote my application on lined paper! (LAUGHS) And dozens and dozens of people applied for the job. This is the other twist, this is the other bizarre twist \endash 
 and I tell this to students in Brunel, because they ask me why did I get in gypsies, and how did I get the job and all that \endash  I went to the Oxfo
rd public library, which is now mainly the Town Hall, a beautiful place, and I realised, in the job description, that this woman had been responsible for the first census for gypsies, and there it was on the shelves. I\rquote 
ve used that in a letter to Keith Mitchell, saying, \'93This changed my life\'94
. I read the Report - the Ministry for Housing and Local Government, published in 1968/69. I went for the interview, and there were two things that helped me. One was I was the only person who\rquote d actually read the Report
, so I showed curiosity, and literally, you know, I applied for the job and I was interviewed two weeks later. And then a friend of my sister\rquote s, a philosopher who Elaine was at Trinity with, he got a brilliant First in philosophy, and he\rquote 
d done work with Irish travellers, but his degree was in philosophy, and he didn\rquote 
t get the job. Anyway, when, at the end of the project, after two and a half years, this woman, Barbara Adams, a civil servant seconded from the Department to work for the Centre on this project, she said, \'93
Would you like to throw out these files, and your references, and your application?\'94 And I hadn\rquote t used Stephen Lukes, I\rquote d used Brian Wilson who\rquote d taught me sociological theory, who was terrified of women. I mean, he\rquote 
d have me in his room and take my coat off, and hang it up, and he was terrified! Gentlemanly, you know. He was closet gay actually. And I couldn\rquote t believe the reference. It was utterly mediocre. \'93She works hard, and she\rquote s well-meaning
\'94, and, \'93She\rquote s not going to set the\'94 - he didn\rquote t put it that way, but it was devastating. As you and I know, a reference like that would never get anybody a job, because you read between the lines, and the last line was, \'93And she
\rquote s a very charming young lady\'94. And my civil servant said, \'93I chose you (a) because you\rquote d read that Census; (b) you were a social scientist\'94, she was terrified of a philosopher, \'93 and (c) - what\rquote 
s the word they used for David Kelly, it\rquote s a negative word about academics. It\rquote ll come back to me. You see, with this age, you forget words! But the implication was that I wouldn\rquote 
t be a challenge to her, and that I would do as I was told. I wasn\rquote t a boffin, that\rquote s right! \'93You weren\rquote t a boffin\'94. Actually, I told this woman, Sarah, this, and she said, \'93God, that woman got you! She didn\rquote t kn
ow who she was going to get!\'94 (LAUGHS) So it was the mediocrity. If I had Stephen Lukes saying, \'93She wrote the best essay I\rquote ve ever heard on Marx\'94, and \'93she was brilliant\'94, and \'93she could have got a First\'94, I wouldn\rquote 
t have got the job! So it was the mediocrity of Brian Wilson that got me the job. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
