\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Yes, yes. I\rquote 
ve written a few notes. Yes. Well, this is where - I was thinking through it last night, that I was appointed, really, she said because I was a social scientist. I said, a friend of my sister\rquote s who had a First
 Class Degree in Literature, and he was Irish, really he might have had a better chance in terms of classification, but I realised, slowly, that she appointed me because she was secure with a social scientist. PPE, it didn\rquote 
t matter what class of degree \endash  although I said in my revision to you, that would now be a II:ii, because they had I, II, III, IV, and then they divided, and I was borderline. Anyway, the viva ruined me. But she also, I realised, thought, \'93
Anthropology deals with the exotic, so it\rquote s useful to have somebody who knows about the exotic\'94. But then she didn\rquote t know or think through how I wanted to do this research. I\rquote ve written about it quite a lot, it\rquote 
s in the book Thinking Through Fieldwork, and I\rquote m terribly proud because part of it\rquote s reproduced in an Open University primer, Doing Social Research. It\rquote 
s terribly interesting with Open University, they ask you questions, they ask the reader question, \'93Why did Judith Okely do this?\'94 Or \'93do that?\'94 Anyway, I was seated in this shared office, in a wonderful Regency building in Regent\rquote 
s Park \endash  Nash Terrace \endash  and I was just given this pile of local reports on gypsies. That\rquote s fair enough, you would think, as it were, get the literature. But she was the main author of The First Census, which the Ministry h
ad tried to stop publishing because it was seen as sympathetic, too sympathetic, and that\rquote 
s why she seconded herself from the Ministry of Housing to do research at the Centre for Environmental Studies, with David Donnison as the Head. They were good buddie
s, he was into housing. I began to read this stuff, and, of course, I was very quickly realising I was reading about stereotypes. You know, they\rquote re the real gypsies, they\rquote 
re the half-blooded. Half-blooded, I thought we got over this in the 18th century! And then there were the pikies and the diddicoys, and then there were the Irish tinkers, and they had this whole gamut. You know, there\rquote s 20% Romanies, and they
\rquote re polite, they pick up their rubbish, and they\rquote re nice, and they\rquote ve got brown eyes. Then the Irish tinkers, who are right at the bottom, and they leave rubbish, and they steal, and they\rquote 
re criminals. Which, by the way, has had a new revival after that film, The Big Fat Gypsy Wedding. And then she thought I was understanding the truth. I say I should 
be very very grateful to her, because the woman did learn. She had contacts around the country, and then she said \endash  I think it was October - oh no, it was perhaps a month after being appointed \endash  she said, \'93
Well, I can give you an introduction. Go to Hertfordshire.\'94 By the way, I never published [the name of] that County, it\rquote s in my Ph.D., which was banned for 30 years, and nobody\rquote s realised now it can be read. But I\rquote 
ve never mentioned the place in any publications because people might work it out. But it makes people vulnerable. And she said, \'93There\rquote s Don Byrne.\'94 Again, I\rquote m very grateful to him \endash 
 he was a very liberal-minded Local Authority guy, employee, who had tried much more liberal policies towards gypsies, and that was when the 1969 Act was about to be enforced, but it wasn\rquote t going to be made law until about \rquote 
71, and he had allowed a temporary site to be kept open near St. Alban\rquote s. I do have a wonderful photograph of that site. You know the book Writing Culture, Clifford and Marcus, there\rquote s several articles where they say, \'93
The anthropologist gains authority by saying, \lquote I was there\rquote \'94. The use of \'93I\'94 is not really autobiographical, it means, \'93When I was doing this\'94
, it gives authority. So I, invariably, in many many lectures, both introduction to first year, and I gave one in Bristol about six weeks ago, to the Archaeology Department, and there\rquote 
s this photograph. I managed to get it a year afterwards, Barbara Adams \endash  that was my boss \endash  her husband was an amateur photographer, and we went round taking photographs, and we posed right up on a hill overlooking the roundabout \endash 
 it\rquote s actually in my book, and there is the long distant view of this. That was the second site where I lived, that\rquote s the second site, but anyway, there\rquote s my caravan, and I can say, \'93That\rquote s where I lived\'94
. It really takes the wind out of people when they say, \'93You don\rquote t know who these thieves and animals are\'94. But anyway, it was another site, I realised, it was \'93Cotlands Wick\'94, I put that down for the record. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
