 and the one I lived on, I can\rquote t remember which is which, but I think it\rquote s the County had the obligation to provide the sites. If I\rquote ve got it right \endash  it might be one way or the other \endash 
 but the gypsies had landed on this triangular patch between dual carriageways, which nobody would want, and the City Council sued the County Council for allowing an i
llegal site. Don Byrne took it through the courts, and they won the case, because they said, \'93We need these temporary sites until we have the duty to provide permanent sites\'94, and then they said, \'93
You can have the site if you have a resident warden on it\'94. So anyway, Barbara said, \'93Go up to Hertfordshire, and there\rquote s a voluntary worker\'94. Actually, she was teaching part-time and paid partly by the Council \endash 
 Penny Vinson, and I mean, it\rquote s a momentous trip! I took a train from St. Pancras Station, arrived I think it was at St. Alban\rquote 
s. Penny met me, and she, of course, was aware of all these things, she just sat down with me in the car, her little Mini \endash  they always joked about her with her Mini \endash  and she said, \'93We\rquote ve got to appear to be friends. It\rquote 
s no good me saying you\rquote re a researcher. How old are you? How many sisters/brothers do you have?\'94 You know, \'93Tell me a bit more about your private life, so then I can introduce you as a friend. It\rquote s no good saying you\rquote 
re a researcher from the Centre for Environmental Studies\'94
. So we sat down, swapped a bit of notes, and then we drove straight off, on to this camp, and I was introduced to Norman McCabe, the Warden, because it was the obligation to be there, and he was incredibly open. Then I realised that he wanted to 
talk, because he had all this amazing information that he wanted to share. And he kept saying that he wanted to go back \endash  he wanted to train as a priest, and then he dropped out, and so he said he\rquote 
d just answered this advert, and that was it. It was, again, a chance for him. And he said he wanted to go back to Ireland for two weeks for a holiday. And I said, \'93Well, why can\rquote t I take your place?\'94 And he said, \'93Hey! That\rquote 
s a good idea!\'94 But meanwhile, that was later arranged, but anyway, I made such perfect contact, and then Penny drove me off to a few other sites \endash  of course, there weren\rquote t residents wardens \endash  and she would say, \'93
Hello, this is my friend Judith\'94, and then on the mini trip back, I would ask her lots of questions. And I said, the \'93Gorgios\'94 \endash  because that\rquote s the word they use for non-gypsies \endash  they were pouring out with information. }{
