\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
No. A year before, or more, a Gorgio, yobbo, was visiting the site, and just backed, at full speed, in the middle of the site - which no gypsy would do, because there was a circle, and gypsies had a circle, and the children would play in the centre - and 
h
er lovely little two-year old was run down and killed. And she was still in desperate mourning, and I was saying that she welcomed me. It was in that first site when I was there for the two weeks. They had a caravan, but they had a old burnt out van, no w
heels or anything, and they cut a hole in the roof so they could have a coal fire, or some burner, and she would invite me there, and we\rquote 
d be talking till two in the morning, as she went over and over the horror of when he was taken to the hospital, and the baby was wrapped up in a sheet after he\rquote d died, and they had to walk past the waiting people, and she said, \'93
They treated my baby like a pillow and he was my boy\'94. So then that was when she started telling me about fortune telling, and I\rquote ve never had, bef
ore or after, any such amazing detail, which became the core of the article in Own or Other Culture, on fortune telling. She told me how she told fortunes, and that she had her little other boy, John, sit next to her, so he\rquote 
d learn what to do. And I explai
ned it to myself, and later impressed - it was actually very good psychotherapy. But the interesting thing is that the outsider is actually somebody to be welcomed by specific people. Now Barbara Adams would say, later, a year into the field, \'93We
\rquote re not getting real gypsies. We\rquote re not getting typical gypsies. The people who talk to you most are those who\rquote ve lived in a house\'94
. Now Jean, her father was a gypsy, her mother was a Gorgio, she was brought up in a council house, she didn\rquote t join the road until she 
was 18, when she married, and her father was a great horse dealer, and she was literate, but she said to me - and I found it in the notes - she said, \'93I sympathise with you, because you were making the same mistakes as I did\'94
. And that was the key thing. Barbara kept thinking, with good old positivism, that you\rquote ve got to find the typical informant to find the uncontaminated culture, whereas I realised that the people that were most articulate were those who\rquote 
d seen both sides, so they could express the difference. They were hybrids. The one man later, whose wife allowed me to go out alone in his lorry to the scrap yard at Waltham Cross, he\rquote d been in the Army. He\rquote 
d been in the Second World War. I think he\rquote d been in a camp, a Holocaust camp, and he was literate, but he\rquote 
d taken to the road. And so he loved talking about these things to me. So anyway, those things. But going back to the questionnaire, my heart sank. I thought, \'93This will ruin my relationship. I will immediately be identified as a researcher\'94. I kn
ew that this was all wrong. So I gave it to Penny, who agreed to do it \endash  I wasn\rquote t there \endash 
 she administered it to some of the families that she knew, and it was wonderful, because what she said was, she knew that many of the answers were lies. Like, \'93Have you been married before?\'94 She knew they\rquote d been married before. \'93
No, no, no, gypsies marry for life\'94. But she had to put down what they\rquote d chosen to tell her. And then it was an own goal, because then when Barbara looked at these questionnaires, she said, \'93It\rquote s chaos. It can\rquote t be coded\'94
, because she could see the inconsistency. Even within the course of the interview they would contradict what they\rquote d said at the beginning. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
