\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Yes. It\rquote s been reprinted. And I was asked to be a keynote speaker at some post-graduate anthropologists\rquote 
 two day event, about four years ago, here in Oxford, and I was a discussant as well, on the papers. I mentioned this article, and the students just clamoured, they crowded round me, they\rquote d never heard of it. They\rquote re so clever, they said, 
\'93We can find it on Google\'94 or whatever, and David Gellner came up afterwards \endash  he\rquote s now a professor there, he\rquote s got Evans-Pritchard\rquote s famous chair \endash  and he said, \'93Leach was ahead of everybody\'94
. The point, the crux of that article is that Leach had done over a year\rquote s fieldwork in one village called \'93Pul Elia\'94 (?? \endash 
 sp. 30.28), and he was looking at a report based on a survey of 52 villages. Ironically, one of the authors was a certain man called Tambiah, who was then a sociologist, and I think it was Leach\rquote s infl
uence that transformed Tambiah later into an anthropologist, whose lectures I followed in Cambridge. And Leach showed the wonderful argument that the one intensive study shows the system, the system, and numbers and all that don\rquote 
t show the system. They concluded that the majority of people in these 52 villages were landless peasants, and Leach said, \'93
I know, from studying the one village, I know the inheritance system, and the majority of those so-called landless peasants are going to inherit\'94. So they\rquote re not landless peasants, you know. Just simple things like that. Of course, I didn
\rquote t have any of that argument to defend me, I just knew instinctively, with this Barbara, that I was suddenly getting there. I was getting these insights. But I\rquote d been inspired by Malinowski \endash 
 I said that before. The anthropologist pitches his or her tent in a village. And again, always with introductory lectures, I put that photograph \endash  the famous photograph of Malinowski\rquote s tent in the Trobriand Islands. And, incidentally, I had
 an e-mail, six months ago, from a woman who I taught at Essex, out of the blue \endash  Pauline Lane. She\rquote s probably very very quiet, she was a mature student, she was a nurse. She\rquote 
s now a top person in the health thing. And I had this amazing meeting with her last July, and she lives near Colchester, and she went on to do a Ph.D. with Ted Benton, and she looked at indigenous patents of medicine. And she said to me \endash  I couldn
\rquote t believe it! She said, \'93I went to New Guinea, and I hired a helicopter to go to the Trobriand Islands\'94 (LAUGHS), and she said, \'93I thought of you as I landed, because I remember your lectures on Malinowski\'94. I thought, \'93
You should have said, \lquote I thought of Malinowski\rquote \'94. She said, \'93No, no, I thought of you when I landed!\'94 But anyway, we\rquote re in communication. It\rquote s lovely just to find these voices \endash  you probably get that as well. }{
