\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Oh, it\rquote s all been challenged. I address it in my book, Tala Asad, who was at Hull
, not when I was there. So people would come up to me and say, \'93God! You were in Tala Asad\rquote s Department\'94
. Anthropology and the Colonial Encounter, he edited a book on that, that made his career for life. He went straight off, snapped up by the States. But he discusses all that about it, and I can\rquote 
t remember all the details now, just offhand, but there was a very good article which I quoted, by Wendy James \endash  a student of Evans-Pritchard, who\rquote s Emeritus Professor here \endash  she did work in the Sudan, and she said
 that the anthropologists actually saw themselves on the side of the indigenous people, but they were na\'ef
ve because they thought Colonialism was much more long-lasting, and that they were there for a barrier between the worst aspects of Colonialism and the people\rquote 
s beliefs. I know that one has to defend - well, not defend, no, no. I mean, Perry Anderson wrote a critique of Evans-Pritchard. It seems that Evans-Pritchard was allowed access to the Nuer because the British Colonialists were puzzled about the ri
se of charismatic leaders. Normally they were a flat society without hierarchies and these charismatic leaders were building pyramids, and Perry Anderson says that Evans-Pritchard just says, in a footnote, \'93The British blew up the pyramid\'94
. And you see all the Colonial Officers who were thanked in the Preface. But the other irony is that many of the Colonial Officers were, again, on the side of the indigenous people. We can see this now, with NGOs. People say, \'93
NGOs are really working for the World Bank\'94, or \'93international capitalism\'94, and there\rquote s that same dilemma. But, I was honoured, I gave, just over a year ago, a Memorial Lecture for my soul sister, Obi Igwara \endash 
 a Nigerian colleague at Hull \endash  who tragically died in 2001, and there\rquote s a lecture in her hon
our every one or two years at the LSE, and I knew that there was a conflict about appointing me, but I had been to every single lecture, and I think they were pretty impressed that I was so loyal. Her ex-boyfriend, who hated anthropologists, they\rquote 
d broken 
up, but he visited Obi in Hull, he was a lecturer in sociology - he refused to have dinner with me because I was an anthropologist, because I was a racist! He tried to block my selection. And sure enough, there were only three anthropologists in the lectu
re hall afterwards when there were questions. And there was this guy, he just read out, \'93Can you explain why anthropologists have colluded with Colonialism and the destruction of Africans?\'94 He was reading it out. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
