\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Yeah, well, I didn\rquote t have to. In my Anthropology and Autobiography book, I reproduced this photograph \endash 
 and that was taken by Barbara\rquote s husband, because we went to different locations and said to the people, \'93Do you mind if we take photos of you?\'94 And I was with this woman, Beatrice, who actually lived in a tent, and I said th
at I unconsciously \endash  when I looked at that photo ten years later \endash 
 she had agreed to be photographed, and Diana Allen, the lawyer, facilitated the photographer. Beatrice knew me, and I said, years later, I realised that she had got the barrier pose, meaning, \'93
I agree to be photographed because Diana Allen has helped me a lot with the legal cases, but this is a stranger\'94. He was called Turner, he wasn\rquote t Adams, it was her pre-married name. And I\rquote d imitated her posture of the barrier - again, I
\rquote ve got an article called \lquote Fieldwork Embodied\rquote , where I\rquote 
ve drawn on my interviews showing how they learn with the body. Again, that was the wonderful thing about fieldwork, you escape from the desk and the library, so I acted with my body. But then the breakthrough came w
hen I moved on to the other site, and again, the people that befriended me were sort of in between. In fact, they were half show people, and Rina, she\rquote d run away from her husband, and she\rquote 
d been married into really big circus/show people, she said they were huge bungalows in a great circle, and she\rquote d escaped, with her child, and she was living with her mother, \'93Aunt Doll\'94
 and the husband, who had his own lorry, and they were literate, and show people are literate. And Aunt Doll wore glasses, which was very unusual. She said, when I first moved on the site, they said, \'93Oh, my God! Here\rquote s the Welfare\'94
, because she wore glasses! And then, how did it happen? I mean, I needed, I had to learn to drive. I hadn\rquote t even learnt to drive then. I took driving lessons, an
d then thanks to this grant, I was able to buy a vehicle, but mind you, it was cheap, I got it at an auction, it was a 15cwt van, and I said I was picking up what I\rquote 
d learnt in Ireland. Actually, it was an ex-police van, so I knew it would be in perfect nick, but it looked old, and actually, they were pretty suspicious when they saw it! (LAUGHS) But I thought, \'93That\rquote 
s it! I learnt from you, which is go out to work!\'94 So I said, I said, \'93I\rquote ve got this van\'94, and I said to Aunt Doll, because they were stuck, be
cause the husband, the older man, he was - I mean, it was just a non-marriage really, he would disappear and go out all day. And I said, \'93I\rquote ve got this van, would you like to go out calling with me?\'94 And they all - \'93Oh, Judy! Oh, great!
\'94, so then I took them out. Then when we arrived back with the first load of old batteries and scrap - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
