\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Yeah, you go to doors, and, of course, they knew the areas, or they would spot them. They\rquote d say things like \endash  I\rquote 
ve said it in an article \endash  \'93Judith, cor, those are nice houses there!\'94 And I was thinking, \'93Yeah, they\rquote ve got lovely interiors\'94, and what they meant was \'93nice for calling, for getting, they\rquote ll be rich people\'94. So you
\rquote d go round amazing areas in Hertfordshire. I, of course, wanted to stand next to Aunt Doll or Rina, and watch how they performed. They were time and motion people, they said, \'93Judith, you\rquote 
re wasting time. You go over and call there, and we\rquote ll call at this door\'94, you know, \'93because we\rquote ll get extra\'94. Of course, I didn\rquote t say, \'93I\rquote m an anthropologist finding out how you do it\'94. I\rquote 
ve lived off these jokes for years \endash  I\rquote ve got them in an article that you know about \endash  but, it was this amazing enclave of private houses, I mean there were lots and, you know, the women - I\rquote d try and drop my \'93H\rquote s\'94
 and extend my vowels, and say, \'93You got any old scrap, any old rags?\'94 you know, like that, and the women would say, \'93Oh, what\rquote s it for?\'94 (LAUGHS) And I looking at people like the mothers of my school friends (LAUGH
S), and in the end I said, \'93Oh, Save the Children Fund\'94. And then I came back to them, and they said, I said, \'93Do they ask you what\rquote s it for?\'94 \'93No, they never ask what\rquote s it for!\'94 \'93Did they ask you, then?\'94 And I said, 
\'93Yeah!\'94 And they said, \'93What did you say?\'94 And I said, \'93Oh, Save the Children Fund\'94. \'93Hey, Judith\rquote s on to a good one there\'94. And then when I said, \'93Save the Children Fund\'94 to one of the other places, she said, \'93
Oh, I\rquote m Secretary of the Local Branch\'94! (LAUGHS) And I gave a friend\rquote s address in Hemel Hempstead, and I told them, \'93I said it was the Hemel Hempstead branch and I gave Connie\rquote s address\'94. \'93Judith, we always say \lquote 
Three Beech Drive. We always say that\rquote s our address\rquote \'94. But it was, honestly, I said it was a liberation. A liberation. But I saw however bungling, just as I\rquote 
ve said in my chapter on participant observation, you never perfect the skills that the people have, but you learn also, crucially, you learn through your mistakes, and you learn to admire those skills. But when we came back wi
th the van, and we unloaded things, they said, \'93Judith, we\rquote re gonna rip.\'94 The other gypsies were all jealous because they hadn\rquote t had the idea of using me. And then they said, \'93We\rquote re going to report you, because you\rquote 
re earning money on the side\'94, because they still thought I was a Council employee. But I never said that. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
