\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 I joined the potato gang, picking potatoes. And again, I\rquote ve said this several times in recent lectures, that the gypsies were
 responsible for most of the fruit picking and agricultural seasonal work in this country, and it\rquote s because of the controls on movement, thanks to John Major, 1994, Criminal Damages Act, that the gypsies are less mobile. They daren\rquote 
t move. So now we have slave labour from Ukraine and wherever, who are living under plastic sheeting, at below the legal wage, doing all the fruit picking and the potato picking, and it was the gypsies work. And, you know, there\rquote 
s that guy, Ewan Somebody, who\rquote s on Radio 4 Today programme, with big sticky out ears, he did one programme about the \'93lazy, white working-class in East Anglia\'94, and they didn\rquote 
t pick carrots or peas, and the Bulgarians did. I actually rang up to complain. I said did he realise that it was the gypsies who did all that work up to the nineties. But he wouldn\rquote 
t know, he just said that it was lazy working-class people on welfare. But it was the fact that the local officials have created a problem where the gypsies would come with their caravans and park, the farmer didn\rquote 
t have to provide accommodation. They came with their families. And the other thing that nobody realises is that, I think it may still be the law, technically, gypsies didn\rquote t have to go to school in the summer, because they were allowed to travel 
with their parents for agricultural work, so the State recognised that. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
