\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 I\rquote ve said, somewhere, that I was visiting a woman, a family, on the side of the road, and they\rquote 
d been given an order for an arrest or something else, and when they showed it to me, it was absolutely terrifying, \'93You will do six months in prison\'94, or \'93Your children will be taken away if you continue to park here.\'94 She couldn\rquote 
t read it, and she screwed it up and threw it away. And I thought, \'93She\rquote s free!\'94 I read it, and it was absolutely terrifying. And so I saw that to be non-literate, you were actually free o
f that hegemony. I only very very rarely did that sort of thing. I took the odd woman to hospital, a woman who was pregnant, and that was the amazing thing, one of them, as I drove her back - they didn\rquote 
t have proper scans in those days, but they said there was a possibility she was expecting twins. And I was fascinated at her saying, \'93I don\rquote t want twins! Oh God!\'94, and all I could think of was Evans-Pritchard\rquote 
s article about twins amongst the Nuer, where they put them in the river because they say they\rquote re hippopotamuses, that they\rquote re not - this is an accident of nature, so they actually drown them, they\rquote 
re redefining them as hippopotamuses, and there\rquote s a famous article about twins. And so, of course, my ears are out! \'93Cor, she doesn\rquote t want twins!\'94 \'93Does this fit with Evans-Pritchard?\'94 (LAUGHS) And then she said, \'93
I know that there\rquote s some people in Africa that drown their babies!\'94 And I thought, \'93My God, she isn\rquote t literate, but she knows Evans-Pritchard on the Nuer!\'94 (LAUGHS) She said, \'93No, no, it\rquote s the double workload\'94
, which is perfectly - anyway, it didn\rquote t turn out to be twins. But when you offer to do something like that, you would get narrative. That was it, if you were helping, then they would unfold. Like I said Jean was telling me about fortune telling w
hich was actually therapy that she was giving to people. I was being her therapist by just listening, because the people said, \'93You should have forgotten about it\'94, and \'93no photographs of the dead should be in the caravan\'94, and she kept 
\endash  in those days, no cameras \endash 
 one tiny little photograph of this dear little blond boy with his back to the camera. All she had was his little blond back of the head, and it was on a frame, in the caravan, and the other gypsies were shocked, because you mustn\rquote t have the dead
 in the caravan. She said, \'93I know I shouldn\rquote t have that photo, because they said the dead will come back\'94, and she said, \'93Well, I want to see him one more time\'94. It was desperate. Absolutely desperate, really. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
