\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 They\rquote re linguists and ironically, in that chapter, I deferred to a man called Ian Hancock, I was deferring to his expertise. He
\rquote d written an article, he was exploring the thing then, he wrote an article saying, \'93Is Anglo-Romany a Creole?\'94, which is a very interesting theme. I\rquote d taken that up, and I thought, \'93Yeah, p
eople say you can trace the route by the words that they use\'94. If there\rquote s a Turkish word, then that means they were there then. It\rquote 
s just nonsense, you know! I first tried that idea out before I put it in my book. That was at this big conference. I publish
ed that one. But The Traveller Gypsies, it was about 1978 I was invited to address a major conference on archaeology at Cambridge, and I was with distinguished company \endash 
 one Eric Hobsbawm, and Edmund Leach. It was a two-day thing, and that was the first time I explored the idea. I used the Malinowski term which is \'93origin myth\'94. It doesn\rquote t mean it\rquote s made up, but Malinowski talks about how \'93
everybody has an origin myth\'94, the Trobrianders thought that people came out from a rock and like Adam and Eve \endash  I call that an \'93origin myth\'94. It didn\rquote 
t mean it was a lie, it was just mythology. Again, you see, Yarron Matras, she says, \'93All gypsies make up things\'94. The venom of two pages in that is unspeakable. But I quoted Leach later, because he was discussant, and he re
ally loved my idea that gypsies were recruited with the collapse of feudalism, alongside people who might have brought the language, but they weren\rquote t a distinct bounded group. Because everybody said \'93
The myths used to be, in the 19th century, they followed the sun\'94, or, \'93What made them leave India?\'94 as if there was one event. Ian Hancock is deeply embarrassed by the fact that I used that article of his, and he\rquote 
s now risen up as a megastar, he\rquote s Professor of Romany Studies in Texas, he has his own fiefdom, and he\rquote 
s ... quoted a very early amateur article of mine, gypsy - Roma language is not a Creole. Well, he presented it, and that was his first article. ... I just want to say one more thing about the view of gypsies, is that when I was employed by the Centr
e for Environmental Studies \endash  and incidentally, you said the panel were impressed because I got the Census out of the library, it was only Barbara who interviewed me, there wasn\rquote t a panel. They\rquote d got the job, but they hadn\rquote 
t yet got the grant for the money. The Centre was financed 50% by the Department, well it wasn\rquote 
t Department of Environment then, and the Ford Foundation, which is supposedly independent. It was full of people doing traffic and housing, and I met up with a certain Mike Harloe, who is later
 on the Appointments Committee! You know, we were undergrads. together in the Labour Club. And he was at the Centre for Environmental Studies, working with Townsend, wasn\rquote t he? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
