I know. Well, there we are, there was another one! Anyway, but this is the way things were done. But all these wonderful radicals, including a famous geographer called Doreen Massey, they didn\rquote t go as a petition,
 but they went to David Donnison protesting that there was going to be their money going to be spent on gypsies. And Doreen Massey took me out to lunch, trying to find out what sort of person I was, and she said, \'93
Well, of course, we all protested about your appointment because the gypsies are only a minority, and we want to look at majorities\'94
. This woman was, at the time, helping people, American conscripts, escape from fighting in Vietnam, and she was sheltering them in a house \endash  now, that\rquote s a minority, an elite minority. But she said, \'93They were only gypsies\'94. Now she
\rquote s a megastar in geography about urban this, and minorities, and multicultural - I was just speechless when she said that. But anyway, the way things are done, David Donnison knew the top person \endash  Head of the Rowntree Memorial Trust \endash 
 he had lunch with him, and over lunch, money was given for the gypsy project, and for hypothermia amongst the aged, and it was Malcolm somebody who became a Minister later, in the Labour government \endash  he\rquote s still an MP \endash 
 Malcolm somebody - so the two of us got grants. So all the protests died down, because it was Rowntree money and it wasn\rquote t our money from the Ford Foundation. So that was one thing about the shock of the hostility, the radicals, the linguists, and
 then the sociologist, Thomas Acton, he was doing a Ph.D., I said in Nuffield, he\rquote s actually a Baptist preacher (LAUGHS), so I just absolutely - I don\rquote t know what I said, \'93I didn\rquote t pick gypsies, they picked me!\'94 }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
