\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Yes. Yes. Well, I\rquote d just like to say, yeah, I\rquote ll say about the notes, because I\rquote 
ve written this, again, in this article that\rquote s in press with a German journal, is that there was nothing on how to write field notes, absolutely no literature. I\rquote ve got shelves upstairs, my study above here, is just lined with 
books on fieldwork methods [but on] writing field notes and all that, absolutely nothing. But I did write, after my first two weeks, a report on Cottons Wick site, but what I did was have headings like, \'93travel\'94, \'93kinship\'94
, whatever, I was deciding, in advance, what to record. That was a report to Barbara to show that I was doing something, because she was worried, she thought, \'93Why is this woman staying there? I\rquote m losing control of her. You\rquote 
ve got to come back to the office\'94. And that was when I thought, instinctively, is there any guidance about writing field notes? Nothing. There\rquote 
s a lovely quote there, Malcolm McLeod, that same lovely person that taught me in my third term at Cambridge, who I\rquote d known from CND days at Oxford, and I\rquote ve interviewed him for my book, and he\rquote s absolutely thrilled, he\rquote 
s read the draft, I said, \'93Malcolm, can you give me any advice?\'94 I visited Cambridge, because my boyfriend then was at King\rquote s, Cambridge, and he just said, wickedly, \'93Judith, you\rquote ve got to write down everything you
 see, you smell, you hear, and you should, ideally, fill up an exercise book for every day\'94. And that was the best and the only advice I got. Of course I couldn\rquote 
t fill up a whole exercise book every day, but that was the thing where you did not decide, in advance, what was relevant \endash 
 which again is consistent with my scepticism of questionnaires, because you decide, in advance. I gave a description of a woman, in the first two weeks, wearing an apron. Little did I know that an apron was crucial in terms of 
their pollution beliefs, and the apron was to shield the genitalia from the food. It\rquote s nothing to do with keeping your clothes clean, it was a symbolic barrier. And then I went back and I thought, \'93God, they\rquote ve all got aprons!\'94
 So it was that minutiae that - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
