\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Well, that was the great thing again, Barbara was finally convinced. I mean, I must admit I was so desperate at one point, because s
he kept saying, \'93You\rquote ve got to know these people, you\rquote ve got to move on to another area now\'94. You know, five weeks, \'93Go on. Now you\rquote ve got to go to Wales. Then you\rquote ve got to go to Lancashire\'94
. And I would invent excuses about \endash  well, it was true \endash  that new families were coming on board. So she gradually - and then she began to look at the field notes. But I\rquote m amazed at my Machiavellian strategies \endash 
 I invited people who I knew believed in fieldwork, and I invited Hugh to come to meet her at the Centre for Environmental Studies, and by this time he was looking at Native Americans in Canada. I don\rquote t know if he\rquote 
d moved on to the Inuit at that point, but he came in and I briefed him. What I did was, I briefed my people beforehand (LAUGHS) and then he would talk a
bout the importance of just picking up what was there. He was a great charmer, and she was totally charmed by him, and very impressed that he\rquote d lived with drunken \'93First Nations\'94 as they\rquote 
re now called in Canada, and probably about to look at the Inuit. There were other people whose names I can\rquote t remember. But then the full apparatus of the Civil Service came into operation, which I said it\rquote 
s been downhill ever since. There was a whole basement of typists down at the bottom of this wonderful Regent\rquote s Park building, they were all typists and they all had to type everybody\rquote 
s letters, including a wonderful woman called Cynthia, who\rquote s very famous now, and honestly I\rquote ll get her name later, but she was doing typing. Actually she was a major urban researcher, but sh
e was earning money to keep her other projects going. So Barbara said, \'93Right. All those notes will be typed\'94
. Then somebody had given her the idea about classification, I think it was another sociologist, she was quite impressed by him. He came and talked to her, he\rquote 
d done urban sociology, and he started talking about sub-classification, and then - pre-computers, pre-Amstrad - 12 photocopies were made of every single typed page with wide margins I read the one typed copy before it was photocopied, and I pu
t comments in loops, like, \'93This is about kinship\'94, and \'93That\rquote s about travel\'94, and sometimes there\rquote d be overlap. And then she employed a full-time research assistant, one of whom is a good friend still \endash  well, we\rquote 
re down to Christmas cards now \endash  but their job was, \'93Right, this week you\rquote re going to look at travel\'94. So there were these copies, say she\rquote 
d had five sheets of the same pages, and the date on every page, and she would cut out every time travel was mentioned, and staple it into a file \endash  and you had 
to several copies because there would be overlap. Ten they did that with the family files. Every time somebody mentioned Matt Chapman or Matt Chapman was talking to me, there were family files, and I\rquote 
ve got them probably in the garden shed out there. So there were all these families\rquote  files for whichthey answered all the questions for the questionnaire \endash 
 their travelling history, their marriage, their work patterns, their literacy. Then she employed a market research man to put all this stuff on the computer for the families, and I met this guy, and he said, \'93My God, this material is utterly amazing!
\'94 And, of course, with bizarre naivety said, \'93Ninety per cent of these families are motorised! This is way beyond the national figure\'94. And I said, \'93Well, they\rquote re nomads!\'94 The other ten per cent, one lot \endash  Beatrice\rquote s 
\endash  they pushed everything in a knife grinding machine. They had their tent, they had prams, and they walked four counties. The irony is that when she did make me travel to another place, I agreed, and I
 went up to Hull, ironically, because that was the one area where there was still horse-drawn wagons in the Humberside. And I met up with Arthur Isaacs who was in the Education Department - we meet just fleetingly at the odd gypsy event now \endash 
 and Arthur took me down to the sites, of the horse-drawn [gypsies]. Of course, there was far more tolerance. If you have a horse, the police aren\rquote 
t going to beat you up and throw you out. So they had far more freedom. I think Farnham Rehfisch was there already, yes, he was, in the Sociology Department, and he\rquote d done the first ethnographic study of gypsies, as far as I know, in Europe. He
\rquote d done work in the Sudan, he\rquote d lived with gypsies in Aberdeenshire, in a tent, and the thesis was in the School of Scottish Studies Archive, and I later discovered \endash  and it\rquote s very revealing \endash 
 that that was a failed Ph.D.. He was one of the Hull - there was a huge Hull lot who all taught in the Sudan, and then they had connections in the Sociology Department, which then became a joint Anthropology. I don\rquote t know if Farnham\rquote 
s book is up there. I\rquote ve got all these books here because \endash  not because I\rquote m showing off \endash  but because I\rquote m supervising an MA student, who\rquote s a New Age traveller \endash  very interesting. He\rquote 
s in his forties. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
