\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Mmm. Well, the other thing was, when I came from Cambridge, we\rquote d been told there were two types of nomads \endash 
 pasturists and hunter gatherers. Hunter gatherers were the Cum (?? \endash 
 94.38) and the Australian aborigines and the pasturists were the Nuer. I must give credit to a wonderful woman, Rina Groper, an American who just wrote the odd article, later she came out with a full book \endash  and 
she started hinting about their migrant goods and services, and I drew on that, and then I said they were a third type of nomad. And then later - there\rquote s this awful word, \'93service nomads\'94, I don\rquote t like it, but that\rquote 
s the category. So my contribution was to emphasise this third type of nomad. Then ironically, with the critique of the Indian origin, after all the venom, there were young researchers all round Europe who loved my ideas, and they said, \'93
Judith Okely was a pioneer in questioning the Indian origin\'94. By the way, I\rquote ve lost track of Hobsbawm. After that conference where Leach had supported me, I found myself on the same railway platform at Cambridge as Hobsbawm. We\rquote 
d already talked over dinner, just quietly, and he said, \'93I was very impressed with your presentation. Would you contribute an article to the journal?\'94 The one on history which he edited. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
