\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 No! No, I mean, somebody, when I was lecturing in the Czech Republic in January, they said, they said, \'93
Marik Karminski, he went working without a Work Permit in Sweden, with the gypsies\'94. I said, \'93For God\rquote s sake! He was stateless, he didn\rquote t have any money. What else could he do but sell a few carpets?\'94 And I said, \'93
Look, what happened was, one gypsy woman, she ran away from her husband\'94 \endash  they were in a Council house - he beat her up, she came and actually stayed in my caravan. Because that was the last caravan. That\rquote 
s how I learnt about death rituals, because it was a local official caravan, and it should have been burnt because an old lady had died in it, and so she insisted on having the windows open, the Calor gas fire on, and all the lights on, and the door open 
all night, to keep the ghost away. Normally, nobody visited me after dark, because they wouldn\rquote 
t want the ghost. But anyway, I was just a Gorgio that you could exploit, so I took her to the Welfare to get some money, because in quite truth, she said, \'93My husband\rquote s beat me up, I\rquote ve left home\'94
. And as we were walking down the streets of St. Alban\rquote s, she went into a smart shop, and I was just waiting outside, and then she came out with a smart plastic bag, not anybody\rquote s bag, but a new one. And she just said, \'93J
udith, you hold on to that for me, will you?\'94 And I was standing on the pavement, holding this thing that I knew was nicked. What could I do? Go back into the shop and say, \'93Look this woman has just nicked it, I want to return it\'94
? How could I? What could I do? I stood there frozen! I was thinking of that wonderful book, The Glasgow Gang Observed, famous book. Then she came out, we walked down the street, and she didn\rquote 
t ask for the bag for about five minutes, and then she asked for the bag, she picked it up and she tore out the tissue paper and threw it down on the pavement as we walked, and I said, \'93Oh, that was a nice free gift!\'94 And she said, \'93
What, you knew it was nicked?\'94 I said, \'93Yeah, of course I knew it was nicked!\'94 \'93Cor, blimey!\'94 Then, as I said to the students in the Czech Republic, \'93
It enhanced my CV, because it said - She goes calling for scrap. She picks potatoes. And she shoplifts!\'94 So it was a wonderful introduction! But I recounted this in the interview with Maurice Freedman and Godfrey Lienhardt, and I thought afterwards, 
\'93But people can talk about headhunting and cannibalism in New Guinea, but, you know, but in the - \'94 Godfrey was so amazing, he said, \'93You won the grant\'94. But it was nothing. Then they put me forward for an SSRC Grant, and iro
nically, apparently \endash  because it would be a Pool Award, they were Pool Awards then, as you know, because they couldn\rquote t give me one just like that \endash  and by chance, apparently even then \endash  and that was still under Labour \endash 
 they were under pressure to show what use these research grants were. And, of course, I had a book just out, or in press, that\rquote 
s right, Gypsies and Government Policy. It was a gift to them. Godfrey is brilliant and he wrote absolutely brilliant references just knowing what the politics was, 
and I got a Pool Award in 1973. I was saved, my fees were paid for, my accommodation. I did try and go back and do more fieldwork, but I found that, again, if you just do day trips or odd things, you\rquote 
re a stranger again. And also things had changed. But, you know, I went back, I kept up in touch, but I was so lucky, because I rented a room in Stile Road, in Headington, because the house I was buying with Jim was being renovated. I can\rquote 
t remember what he was doing, because he then got a job at King\rquote s, London, and so we bought a house together. My mother sold her house in Acton, and gave my sister and I each \'a3
5,000 to put down as a deposit. Those were the days - a house in Islington for \'a312,000! Three storey! Imagine! The seminars, the peer group, the peer group - there was Kirstin Harstrup, Martin Thom \endash  I notice he\rquote 
s somewhere in York now, Kirstin\rquote s a professor in Denmark \endash  Graham Clark, who tragically died But they were amazed at me because I had actually done fieldwork, they were just starting their Ph.D.s.
. And I met up with a wonderful young Frenchwoman in Tours the other week, and she said the same things that I\rquote ve experienced over the years, is that people cannot believe that you\rquote 
ve done work with gypsies, they think you must have a relative. But it was 
that that gave me the freedom, and then I could pursue all - some of those chapters in my thesis and my book, I reduced it, but all the ideas were there. Then I could elaborate on pollution beliefs, because this woman, Barbara Adams \endash  that\rquote 
s another thing about working for a civil servant, is that I had to go up, even when I was writing up, after I\rquote d lived on the gypsy camp, and it was like \rquote 
72 I was writing up, I would want to go to the library, the Kensington Library, with the Gypsy Law Society Magazine/J
ournal, and she made me take a day out of annual leave to go to a library. If I went up to Oxford, it was a day out of my annual leave, to go to seminars. And again, Yarron Matras, who\rquote s Head of the Romany Studies, he said, \'93
Judith Okely dismisses years of scholarship\'94
. I used my annual leave to go to the Gypsy Law Society, but Barbara Adams, again, she thought pollution beliefs are just mumbo-jumbo leftover superstition. But I was able to write that up, and I wrote a lot in that wretched little rented plac
e in Stile Road, with the stimulus of my colleagues. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
