\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 No. No. I mean, again, I was swapping notes with a lovely guy in a conference in Be
lfast. He says he remembers me being invited to lecture to undergrads. at Cambridge years later, and he just said, you know, \'93We were just spellbound that somebody was doing work in Europe, in Britain.\'94 That\rquote s again, the other thing. I
\rquote ve since made friends with a lovely guy, Ahmed al-Shahi (?? \endash  sp. 114.17), still links to St. Antony\rquote s, who absolutely adores Godfrey, he did work in the Sudan. He has inherited all of Godfrey\rquote 
s papers, and we were reminiscing about him. Ahmed absolutely worships him. Ahmed was a Turkish Kurd who got a Scholarship at the age of 18, to come to Oxford. And I said that I didn\rquote 
t realise that Godfrey has an Austrian father and English mother, not Austrian Jewish, and he landed up in Yorkshire, and he feigned, or had a terribly upper class accent \endash 
 I think he had a Yorkshire accent at one point, but he could switch. But when I was swapping notes with Ben \endash  the guy who I met up with at Belfast, who remembers my lecture, as an undergrad. \endash  I said that Godfrey was just amazed that I cou
ld be living with these bizarre, weird, filthy people, just up the road! (LAUGHS) And he started reading my field notes along with his brother Peter Lienhardt, who specialised in Arab society, and one of them had to go off to the loo and vomit, because I 
was talking about clearing - appearing to be useful and picking up newspaper, and then I found a load of human faeces, and they went off and vomited! Godfrey was looking at my field notes at one point, and he said, \'93They\rquote 
re more violent than the Dinka!\'94 (LAUGHS) So we all agreed, Ben and I agreed. Godfrey was so amazed that I could be doing this thing. But I am grateful to Godfrey because he totally supported me, but he was frightened of me at first, and I couldn
\rquote t even get him for any supervision, anything. And originally I was paying for it! But as Edwin said, \'93He didn\rquote t see the money\'94
. But the Institute was sinking in alcoholism, and Godfrey was an alcoholic, he died of liver problems, so did his brother, so did Evans-Pritchard, although Evans-Pritchard part committed suicide \endash  drank himself to death. It was just an all boys
\rquote  thing where you go off to the pub and you get absolutely blootered with booze. Godfrey, he\rquote d been given me because he didn\rquote t obey the rules, and then I came back from a pub, oh, about 
2.30, and I met him in the library, and I think he smelt the alcohol on my breath, and he melted! (LAUGHS) But I\rquote 
ve heard that the reference he wrote for me, for Durham, was absolutely over the top. Then the irony is that when I went to Edwin, because ther
e was a huge split. There were students of Edwin Ardener, they were total disciples, and there were students of Rodney Needham, and the two men wouldn\rquote t speak to each other. Needham even blocked his students going to Shirley Ardener\rquote 
s seminars. I mean, it\rquote s just pathetic! My next book is going to be a campus novel. And I went to Edwin, everybody was looking for the right supervisor, \'93Have you got Edwin?\'94 \'93Have you got Needham?\'94 I went to Edwin, and I said, \'93
Could I change supervisors?\'94 I think I wanted Needham, because Needham had invited me to give \endash  he ran his seminar \endash 
 and again, I mean, they were just incredulous! There was this going on a few miles away. There was a huge Oxford male thing, which I quoted in my book about, shit and dirt and everything, a
nd I used that as the opening to my paper for Rodney Needham, and I said, \'93Look, this is actually pollution beliefs there\'94. And they just were so fascinated that they could see anthropology just up the road! Then I spoke to Edwin, and he said, \'93
No, Godfrey\rquote s been very loyal to you, and you shouldn\rquote t abandon him\'94. Later, I discovered that the students of each of these top men were totally in their hold, and that they had to follow their line, and a wonderful friend \endash 
 I sort of caught up with her on Google the other day, she\rquote s Sierra Leonese \endash  and she was supervised by one person, I won\rquote t say who it is, but she was so bitter - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
