\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Oh yes, the mentors. Yes, well, it was that there was this seminar, apparently a number of women in about 1972 said \endash 
 that was like women\rquote s consciousness-raising \endash  they said, \'93Let\rquote s have a seminar\'94
. One of the pioneers was Charlotte Hardman, who is a lecturer up in Newcastle now. She was a student of Edwin Ardener, and she did work in India or Nepal. So I was parachuted in, because I arrived in about 1973, and I\rquote ve w
ritten about it in an article \endash  and I said that it was like women\rquote s consciousness raising groups. In this tribute to Shirley, I said that at the end of one of the seminars, Shirley said, \'93That was a successful seminar\'94, and I said, 
\'93Why?\'94 And she said, \'93Because everybody spoke\'94. That was incredible. And what we did note, time and time again, was that it wasn\rquote t a cockfight. It\rquote 
s true that there were more men doing anthropology in those days. I mean, social science has become feminised. Politics is - in the Hull Department of Politics, there wasn\rquote 
t a single woman lecturer, nothing, until they got a wife of somebody who was then given a job. And I found that inspiring. I said, for all future post-graduate seminars I ran in future, that \'93I didn\rquote t like cockfights\'94
, and I encouraged people to speak. When we did allow the odd man come into the seminars in Oxford, they would just take over, and they wouldn\rquote 
t even realise they were taking over, and what we found was, it was a sparring match. I was just watching the wonderful film, The Big Country, with Gregory Peck and Charlton Heston, and there\rquote 
s an amazing fight where they go out into the plains and they have a fight till dusk, and I thought, \'93Yeah, that\rquote s a macho seminar for you!\'94 I was asked to speak on International Women\rquote s Day at Warwick, \'93Is Feminism still relevant?
\'94 Amazing, Students\rquote  Union with 300 students, and three of us on the stage with a mike, and I mentioned that as an example, and some of the women came up to me and said, \'93It\rquote s still like that now\'94. But
 that was my strategy. By the way, when I first came to Essex, there was no post-graduate seminar, and I started it, and I chaired the one in Edinburgh later. But I know that some males were very confused and, indeed, the one who I was to testify against 
in the Tribunal, he actually set up some of his male students to mock the women. These men had a contest to see how many times they could mention one particular author \endash  Hastrop, actually, a contemporary of mine \endash 
 and who was going to win, and the woman giving the paper had no idea. And then who was going to win to get her to mention the name. I didn\rquote 
t know that this male lecturer was setting it up. Later, a few years later, I was utterly shocked - a friend of one of my former male students started giggling at some event, and then he wasn\rquote t at Edinburgh, and he said, \'93
Oh, Spencer refers to your male post-grad. students as \lquote Judith\rquote s Eunuchs\rquote \'94. ... The anonymous reader said could I show something more about new forms of fieldwork? I\rquote ve interviewed people who did work in the \lquote 
60s in the \lquote 70s with the Pashtun in Afghanistan, down to a wonderful Franco-Senegalese woman who\rquote s done work on dance \endash  she\rquote s a lecturer in the African Studies here. I interviewed her here. I said, \'93
Does your little toddler, does she have toys?\'94 And she said, \'93She\rquote ll find plenty\'94. So she did find plenty. But I\rquote ve interviewed all those people up to sort of 2005, but then I thought, \'93Hey!\'94 you know, \'93I\rquote 
ll take advantage of this. I\rquote ll put in the titles and some publications of my former Ph.D. students\'94. And there\rquote s one who, a eunuch? He\rquote 
s near 80 now. He ran a Borstal, he was head of a Borstal. They were closed down under Thatcher. He already had a degree in sociology, and self-funded, he came and did an M.A. in Anthropology at Edinburgh, and he got so \endash  I mean, I\rquote 
m diverting, but I just want it for the record \endash  Edinburgh was suddenly classified as the AIDS city of Europe. It\rquote s only because they recorded it. And there was huge medical grants to go and study the AIDS capital of Europe. He was wande
ring down a shopping arcade \endash  and I will send you a copy of my book when it comes out in October - he suddenly saw two guys in their twenties, and they said, \'93Mr. Clive Foster! Hey!\'94 He\rquote 
d been the Head of the Borstal, you see! And they greeted him like a friend. They were HIV positive through injections \endash  heroin. Anyway, he did his Ph.D. on that. And that\rquote 
s another story about trying to get money from the Medical Council or something, in Edinburgh. They kept saying that \'93You don\rquote t have a control group\'94. \'93What\rquote s this? Participant observation? You\rquote 
re mixing with these people? What is this method?\'94 And he had no form of defence, he thought he\rquote d embraced anthropology and this was it! Fortunately, I think this is where Cohen did put pressure \endash  somebody did \endash  and 
in the end they folded. But, do you know, they said he could only get this pittance of a grant as long as the thesis was on the carers of HIV positive people, and not the people \endash 
 because the medics thought they owned these people. And these wonderful guys \endash  again, it\rquote s methods \endash  these wonderful lads, and, of course, some of the kids got HIV positive through childbirth. And they said, \'93
Come on, sir, we want you to write our story, not like all these researchers all round there with their clipboards. We don\rquote t want researchers, we want you to write our story\'94
. They were all besieged with people with clipboards. There was money going out of everywhere. And he did a brilliant ethnographic study of HIV positive drug users. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
