Well, I mean, I said we were all post-grads., and really, it was a chance for people to explore ideas with a confident supportive atmosphere. It wasn\rquote t that we sat down and said, \'93Let\rquote s have this theory or that theory\'94, I think it re
scued people. And dear old Godfrey, he was very worried about Feminism, and he said to somebody, \'93Well, I don\rquote t know what Judith\rquote s doing with this Feminist lot, but she\rquote s brilliant anyway, so she\rquote d get anywhere if she wasn
\rquote t a Feminist.\'94 So that got back to me. But I remember a lovely young woman, I think she was sociology, she\rquote d done work in shanty towns in South Africa, and she gave the most appalling paper. But what happened was that people didn\rquote 
t say, \'93This is rubbish\'94: they asked her questions, and she
 had the answers. And there were 15 questions. She was totally articulate. She went away on a high! And she finished the thesis and she wrote a book, but the actual paper was pathetic. She had the information, but she didn\rquote 
t know what to do with it. But I left. I got the Durham job in 1976, and I still hadn\rquote 
t yet finished my thesis. It was a one-year, a nine months temporary job. My grant had come to an end. So I left it. But that Group has always suffered - I mean, Shirley\rquote s consolidated it and had the Visiting Fellows, but it\rquote 
s now come to a halt, because the head of Queen Elizabeth House says we can\rquote t have Visiting Fellows unless they\rquote re linked to somebody who\rquote s on a salary. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
