s not the Thursday Queen Elizabeth House Gender thing that was in Queen Elizabeth House \'85 and incidentally, that goes back to Maurice Freedman. The reason why it was linked to Queen Elizabeth House was that when Juliet Blair \endash  long deceased 
\endash  and Shirley and Charlotte Hardman asked if they could have an all women\rquote s seminar in the Institute, Maurice Freedman said it would be discriminatory. And yet he was at All Souls that forbade any women even to apply! So he said we couldn
\rquote t have a thing that excluded men. So then, because Edwin and Shirley were linked to Queen Elizabeth house \endash  that\rquote s why it started. But The Friday Seminar, I haven\rquote t been for some - I went two years ago, actually, because I
\rquote m always busy now. You can look up ISCA on the internet now, it\rquote s all very clever, and it\rquote s the kind of ritual where you have outside speakers. So I was invited then, in 1977. But fortunately there\rquote s a sem
inar run by Mohammed Kalib (?? \endash  sp), well, he now says he\rquote s not professor, but we call him \'93Professor of Islamic Studies\'94 in the Centre for Islamic Studies here, and an anthropologist, he\rquote 
s joint running a seminar this autumn. I\rquote ve interviewed him for my 
book as well. What better to have a Muslim Indian who did fieldwork on stone breakers in India! He sat down here, and I interviewed him. And it was terribly moving. As he sat down, he said, \'93I just want to reassure you, I\rquote 
m not a fundamentalist Islamist\'94. I said, \'93Don\rquote t worry! Don\rquote t worry!\'94 (LAUGHS) And I deliberately displayed this! (LAUGHS) And he looked at it, and he said, \'93That\rquote s from India\'94. I said, \'93Yes\'94. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
