\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 No, it was different. I would j
ust like to say one thing, though, that I had to fight to have a course on gender. I want to say two extra things about Durham, which is discrimination against women, is that when I applied for Essex, I didn\rquote 
t put down my class of degree, and the woman, after the interview, stopped me in the passage and said, \'93What class of degree did you get?\'94 I\rquote 
d learnt not to put it in. But I put it down at Durham, and I was given a nine month temporary job, and in those days the CV was circulated throughout the whole Senate, and the Professor of Mathematics said, \'93
This is a disgrace that we are giving a job to somebody with a Third Class degree\'94. What they didn\rquote t notice was that they gave the permanent job to a man who didn\rquote t even have a degree. They didn\rquote t spot it! He w
ent to Teddy Hall to do geography. He dropped out. He didn\rquote t lie, he just put, \'93Studied geography at Teddy Hall\'94
. His father was a Freemason and Head of a College, and later he drifted off to the Caribbean, and he was allowed to come back and do a Master\rquote s in Ethnology, and then he did a Ph.D., and he didn\rquote t have an undergraduate degree! But they didn
\rquote t even notice. They gave him the permanent job. They didn\rquote t even interview me for that. Anyway, dear old David, my lovely colleague \endash  the Scottish guy who did the Baktiari (?? \endash  26.25) \endash 
 he said, he knew how to work the class, he\rquote d got a real sort of Scottish accent, but he banged the table, and he said - his supervisor, by the way, was Peter Lienhardt, here. He said, \'93Gentlemen,\'94 because there was no woman in Senate, \'93
Gentlemen, this lady was first Woman President of the Oxford Union\'94, and he said they all melted! I said, \'93David, it wasn\rquote t President! I was first woman member!\'94 And then, when I came back, two years later, I\rquote d got my D.Phil., I
\rquote d got more publications, I\rquote d swept through, unanimous committee, and I didn\rquote t put down my class of degree then. I\rquote d got my D.Phil., by then, because I got it in \rquote 77. The maths Professor remembered. \'93
Gentlemen, why should we give this permanent job to a woman who has a Third?\'94 And the Vice-Chancellor said \endash  and I know he was repeating David\rquote s words \endash  \'93Gentlemen, this is a very powerful lady\'94
, and that shut them up! (LAUGHS) But, you know, the sort of bafflement that I had to pretend to have broken up. David said, \'93Judith, you\rquote ll have to pretend you\rquote ve broken up with Jim, because if they know you\rquote 
re still commuting to London.\'94 I was taking a train at 5 o\rquote clock at night on a Friday, and taking one at seven on a Monday, and getting there by 10! And when Jim was in the Mental Hosp
ital, he was only allowed out of the Hospital if I was there at home, so I would come maybe on a Friday, and he\rquote d be allowed out for the weekend, and I never missed a class, I never missed a seminar. And I said, you know, \'93
Should I tell the professor that my partner\rquote s seriously ill?\'94 He said, \'93Judith, for God\rquote s sake don\rquote t say it, you won\rquote t get the job\'94. Then you see all these articles about \'93
Is it possible to have a commuting relationship?\'94 Women weren\rquote t even short-listed if they were married! The wickednes
s of it! So, anyway, I thought, when I came to Essex - by the way, I have a filing cabinet full of applications for jobs. every Anthropology Department south of Leeds, and Sociology Departments, so I was amazed that I could be short-listed at Essex. But i
t was always because I\rquote d done work in Britain that I was not a real anthropologist. I would never have got a job at the LSE. And even now they\rquote 
re totally prejudiced. And I keep repeating an interview with Maurice Bloch in the introduction to my Own or Other Culture, where he said, \'93We shouldn\rquote t study Europe, because we know it\'94
. The arrogance of it was just unspeakable! So anyway, I got that. I was lucky. I swept into the job. And dear Lee, she - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
