\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Yes. She met me before the actual interview, I think she welcomed me into her office. She\rquote d never met me. Oh yes, that\rquote 
s right! Yes, because we\rquote d invited her to give a talk on Feminist History in Durham, so I\rquote d met her. That\rquote s right, that\rquote s how I\rquote d met her. And then she invited me into the office, and she said, \'93Judith\'94, she said, 
\'93You\rquote ve got a very good chance here because you\rquote ve published\'94, and apparently my position there was to replace somebody who\rquote d not been given tenure. And so that boosted my morale. So I went in. I had nothi
ng to lose because I already had a job. But it caused uproar with Godfrey, Edwin Ardener. The anthropology world said, \'93You\rquote re absolutely mad!\'94 because Essex had a radical history, and a New University, and \'93Why can\rquote 
t you stay at this wonderful Durham?\'94 And people kept talking about the cathedral. I said, \'93I don\rquote t give lectures in the Cathedral\'94. Do you know, I wasn\rquote t even allowed accommodation. I was told, because I wasn\rquote 
t married, they couldn\rquote t provide me with accommodation, or even membership of a College - because I wasn\rquote t married. And yet you wouldn\rquote 
t be short-listed if you were married. So I told you, did I, I had found this mining village out there. Did I say that? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
