\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Yeah, well, it was just wonderful in that th
e University accommodation said they could not provide anything for me because I was a single woman, and they only dealt with married men. And then they said, \'93Go to the Students\rquote  Union for accommodation\'94. And he said, \'93Since you\rquote 
re a privileged member of staff, we will only give you addresses 12 miles out of Durham. And I hired a taxi \endash  he gave me an address in a mining village, Sherburn Hill \endash 
 and I had a taxi, 12 miles out, to look at an end of terrace mining place. They\rquote re in those amazing villages that are just about four terraces for a pit, and they were \'93D villages\'94
. I got this place, and it was my saviour, because these retired miners just absolutely adopted me. I could drive, I took them to Beamish, they took me to Miners\rquote  Clubs, and I just learnt the whole other side of Durham \endash 
 the mining Durham. That was my saving grace. They would invite me into their houses. And the escape from the horror of that - I never even dined in College, because I wasn\rquote t allowed in College because I was a woman. Anyway, 
I came to Essex, and I thought, \'93God, there\rquote s five women here! Thank God!\'94 But I was disappointed because people didn\rquote t welcome me. But I give it to dear Gordon Marshall, I mean, he was so terrific, because he\rquote 
d done anthropology at Stirling, he knew a bit, and the first week or whenever I arrived, or was it before I arrived? He said, \'93If you want accommodation, you can stay with us\'94. Then by bizarre horror, I\rquote d sold my terraced house in Durham 
\endash  because I did buy a little terraced house, you know, as cheap
 as anything, though I had my place in London - the people who were selling the Dedham cottage delayed for six weeks, so I had to go to dear Gordon and, honestly, what a guy! I stayed there four nights a week for six weeks. I mean, what generosity! Just t
errific! The welcome was just lovely. But I didn\rquote t find any of the women welcoming at all, except later, Alison Scott read my article on the boarding school, and she came to me in tears because she recognised her own life. And she\rquote 
d done anthropology with Jimmy Littlejohn in Edinburgh, and it was very weird, because we were united by rejection of our class upbringing. I think she\rquote 
d been encouraged to go to university, but she went to Edinburgh because she wanted to find her Scottish roots. She was called Alison MacEwan, and that\rquote s when she met Chris Scott. And we became very very close buddies, absolutely terrific. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
