\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Yeah, yeah, well, I mean, she was just busy. She wasn\rquote t hostile. She wa
s wonderfully welcoming, but she was just disappearing under work, but I never \endash  she wasn\rquote t a buddy. But I wanted somebody to support me, especially as the snobby anthropologists said, \'93You\rquote 
ve ruined your career. You should never have left Durham\'94. And then Joan Busfield said, \'93What on earth could you teach?\'94
 And I was put into the Deviancy Course, and Ken was delightful. But this was the other thing, that I had never heard of the term \'93symbolic interactionism\'94. Right towards the end of my time in Essex, I 
met up with Tony Woodiwiss on the train, because he commuted, and he said, \'93Well, of course, we didn\rquote t want you because you were a symbolic interactionist\'94. And I said, \'93What do you mean?\'94 And he said, \'93
Well, you know, you do fieldwork with people. You\rquote re a symbolic interactionist\'94. I said, \'93What?\'94 I said, \'93If you meet people, you\rquote re a symbolic interactionist?\'94
 And, of course, I knew there was a big debate, symbolic interactionism apparently ignored structure and politics and economics, and you looked at whether people\rquote s eyebrows went up or not. I mean, I\rquote d never heard the term. I told Tony, \'93
You can have Marxist anthropologists,\'94 and, of course there was this bizarre division between the Weberians and the [Marxists] - it was just bonkers to me! I looked at 
the economy. But they condemned me without even knowing my work. Ken was a symbolic interactionist, so it was assumed, because I was teaching on the Deviancy Course, that I was one of those that ignored political structures and power. But then I taught on
 the Methods Course, I taught the Qualitative Methods, there was a compulsory course. And I was shocked, because I inherited ... from David Rose, yes, he taught both quantitative and qualitative, and I asked if I could see last year\rquote 
s reading list, and they were very vague about it, and finally I was given a copy, and the key point about qualitative methods was, \'93read lots of novels\'94
. I was just incredulous. But my key text - I said I fought with Barbara Adams over qualitative stuff, and my only key texts th
en were [William Foote-Whyte] The Street Corner Society appendix - absolutely key. That is priceless. The theme of hanging around. And then Ulf Hanners (?? \endash  sp. -40.11), Swedish, who\rquote 
d written a book called, Soul Side, published in 1969, and I\rquote ve interviewed his wife, Elena Woolf (?? Sp. \endash  40.24) for my book, and it was a delight meeting him years later. I said, \'93You don\rquote 
t know what a lifeline your appendix, or fieldwork chapter, was\'94. Because he was inspired by Street Corner Society, and he went to Washington and looked at an Afro-American ghetto in Washington. He was a pioneer on that. I said \'93Those were lifelines
\'94, so I put those on the reading list. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
