\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 He\rquote d done work, I think in India first \endash  he was American \endash 
 and then he went back to America to do qualitative research, I think in the health services or social services, and he met up with all these quantitative people, and they kept saying, \'93What\rquote s your hypothesis?\'94 \'93What is your tool?\'94 \'93
What are you testing?\'94 He said he was totally baffled because he didn\rquote t use that approach when he did anthropological fieldwork in India. I\rquote ve used this \endash  and, I mean, it\rquote s a wonderful joke. He came up with the \'93
funnel method\'94, which was that you\rquote re open to everything, and then you refine it. So I\rquote ve made lots of jokes in lectures saying, the \'93funnel method\'94
 got me the ESRC Grant to do Normandy, it got me the travel grant. Because they kept saying, \'93Can you prove the value of ethnographic methods?\'94 I\rquote d say the \'93funnel method\'94, and it shut them up! (LAUGHS) And I said, \'93It\rquote 
s phallic, it\rquote s hard. It also appeals! It\rquote s a tool!\'94 (LAUGHS) I was lecturing in Nottingham about four years ago, and they said, \'93Thank God, Judith, we\rquote re now going to introduce the funnel method\'94
, it means being open. And there\rquote s a wonderful passage which I used to quote in lectures, I\rquote ve got it in a book, \'93
When you go into the field, you arrive with part of your life history, the latest novels, everything, you go with yourself. You go with everything. And then that is a resource\'94
. Again, talking about my lecture in the Czech Republic where I did an overrun of the book, and my main theme was quotes from the people I\rquote ve interviewed, and I said, \'93Every one of them changed their focus when they were in the field\'94
. So you change your focus, but it\rquote s no good a grant body saying, \'93What hypothesis are you testing?\'94 And the great thing is that when I was helping to fill in ESRC forms, the students would come to me \endash  in Edinburgh \endash  and it wou
ld say, \'93What hypothesis are you testing?\'94 And they were bewildered. And I wrote to the ESRC, and I said, \'93This is not how anthropology works\'94. And now they\rquote ve changed it. I haven\rquote t looked at one recently, but it says, \'93
What research questions?\'94 That\rquote s good, \'93research questions,\'94 you can have these puzzlements and you may change, but a hypothesis - and, of course, I\rquote 
m grateful to you for appointing me, but I also learnt the positivistic side of methods. Because I could see the students being bullied \endash  the undergrads. \endash 
 for a six week dissertation. Joan Busfield was a decent person, but she would be telling these students, \'93How can you operationalise this hypothesis?\'94 I mean, it was a six week event, and that was before Agar, it must have been before Agar. I r
emember, I was absolutely bewildered, because I\rquote d never been told that in Oxford \endash  \'93What hypothesis are you testing when you go off the M1 and live on a camp?\'94 But I have used it as a straw man, because it\rquote 
s made me realise, and I\rquote ve got the whole first chapter - my friend Deborah, the one who\rquote s now got three-quarters of a million to look at mining in Africa, she\rquote s a geographer, she blew her top at my first chapter. The reader says, 
\'93Bring in all the nice examples in Chapter 1\'94. I\rquote m sorry, I have to get it clear, and I sent that chapter to a brilliant Maltese post-grad., and she said, \'93Judith, it\rquote s absolutely essential that you get rid of all this crap about we
\rquote re imitating a fantasy view of what science is\'94. That\rquote s where Stephen Rose is so brilliant. I\rquote ve quoted him, and he talks about \'93physics envy\'94. He says \'93Every discipline\'94
 - and guess what, Lord Browne, who did the Inquiry into the future of universities, his degree \endash  he only has an MA and a first degree \endash  is in physics, so he\rquote s cut all funding for huma
nities and social science, and only science is protected. And what I\rquote ve argued is that anthropologists\rquote 
 methods are scientific - in the broadest sense of the word. So, anyway, Essex was very useful as well by being confronted with this positivism. But what great joy it was that Ted Benton and Ian Craib \endash  and he tragically died \endash 
 they were on the Research Committee for Andy Dawson, and Andy kept thinking, \'93You\rquote ve got to have hypotheses,\'94 even though I told him not. I was away one time when they had a meeting
 with him, and he came to my office, absolutely thrilled, because they said, \'93What\rquote s all this positivistic hypothesis thing?\'94 And what I found so lovely was that the really respectable high theoreticians like Benton and Craib, they didn
\rquote t want any of this nonsense of testing and contamination. I\rquote 
ll tell you a story about Andy. Andy got an outstanding First Class for his dissertation. Frank Bechhofer was the External. Andy, he knows how to network. He got to know the porters, the cleaners, the security men o
n the Essex campus, and anybody over 55 he interviewed about their views of ageing, andwho would do that at Essex? You could be all radical and say, \'93Okely\rquote s a symbolic interactionist, would you even talk to a porter? No!\'94
 And Andy came to me after the Distinction, and he said, \'93Judith, I\rquote ve cheated! I\rquote ve cheated!\'94 I said, \'93What?\'94 (LAUGHS) He said, \'93
I not only interviewed some of those people, but I got them all together in a basement room after work hours in the evening, I gave them bottles of wine and glasses, and I got them all talking together about what it was they felt about ageing\'94
. And then he said, \'93I cut out the quotes and presented them as one-to-one interviews, because otherwise I would have been accused of them contaminating each other\'94, because they were all meeting. He\rquote 
d picked up the notion of contamination from the lectures. I said, \'93Andy, you should have been given an extra star for ingenuity and originality!\'94 And he went away happy! But that was this positivistic notion, which I hope is dea
d now in sociology. But then my student, ex-student, Tony, found that four years ago in Manchester, that you shouldn\rquote t interview people you know because you\rquote ve contaminated them. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
