\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 And they asked somebody else to write - Virago wanted women pioneers, because - was it Frank Commode (?? \endash 
 53.50) had got a series on great thinkers? And it was all male, except perhaps Mary Douglas. And so Ursula Owen said, \'93Let\rquote s have Virago pioneers\'94
. And whoever it was turned down the thing. Rosalind, she was the wife of the person who translated Gramsci\rquote s notebooks - the woman who was first offered it, and then she didn\rquote t want to go ahead with it. And then I just suddenly 
got an invitation to meet Ursula Owen over lunch, and that was it. But I read through all this stuff, and I had all these files, and I had originally a chapter, with notes, saying \'93The historical context of the publication of de Beauvoir\rquote 
s Second Sex, 1949,\'94 and I suddenly realised, \'93I\rquote m not a historian. How can I possibly - I can\rquote t do any original research\'94. And then I just had this eureka moment. The things I underlined were so na\'efve, let\rquote 
s compare the naivety of my thing before Women\rquote s Liberation in 1961, with post-Women\rquote 
s Lib. There was now a huge body of literature. There was Woman Culture in Society; Risaldo and Lampfayer (?? - 55.24 - sp), and by the way, that book, Woman Culture in Society, which was 1975, I think - Louise Lampfayer, she was not give
n tenure at Brown because they didn\rquote t take Feminism seriously, and there was a huge court case, and in the end Brown gave her compensation, but she\rquote d moved to New Mexico, so you know, women\rquote 
s anthropology was not - and then years later, another of my interviewees \endash  Nancy Lindisfarne, who did work with the Pashtun \endash 
 she did a wonderful edited book called, The Limits of Masculinity, I think that was in the eighties, and when she was applying for promotion at SOAS, they ridiculed her and said, \'93This is not anthropology. This is not serious\'94
. So gender was not taken seriously. And then she finally took early retirement at 55 or something. Incidentally, that\rquote s her oil painting of her anger with the invasion, bombing of Aghanistan, after 9/11. She had a whole exhi
bition of anger of the blood \endash 
 she knew more about it that anybody. When did they invade or bomb? It was 2002, if not 2001? And Nancy knew what was coming. She knew. So I thought about this. But I would send letters, I would phone Virago with each draft, and say, \'93
Would you accept that it\rquote s all right to do it this way? \'94 Then, of course, I interviewed, and I looked at other sources, and one of my Ph.D. students at Essex, who was actually from near Calcutta \endash  I\rquote 
m afraid she disappeared without trace, she never finished \endash  she gave me - I\rquote ve got her quote. It was fascinating to see that somebody Indian admired de Beauvoir, not because she was ethnocentric \endash  which I argued \endash  it was that 
\'93we loved it that the Western woman also had problems\'94. That \'93we Indians are not the only ones\'94 -\'85 we\rquote re all told, you know, \'93You\rquote re women, and subordinate\'94
, and then they could find out that, in France, they had their debates. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
