\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 I don\rquote 
t know if I got anything, it was just something that started with the first chapter. This was the context as to why de Beauvoir\rquote s book was absolutely a hit with women, but it was torn apart by the reviewers \endash  male. I\rquote 
ve said that people threw it the length of caf\'e9s and said, \'93Now we know the contents of your vagina\'94. De Beauvoir was humiliated, but what she said was that all through the fifties, she would get letter after letter, of young women saying, \'93
You\rquote ve inspired me\'94. So I was joining that rank of people. It wasn\rquote t just me, as idiosyncratic me, I was an example of somebody who was inspired by that author to go against the grain. But I tried, I didn\rquote 
t want it to be just about me. I said I was just an example of women, in the fifties, who weren\rquote t supposed to be intellectuals or go to university. And it hit the spot in America. So I got lots of quotes, wherever possible \endash 
 I interviewed students or others, so it got beyond me. But then it had its own momentum. With each chapter, I would find - 
and then it just came out. But how did I arrive at it? Having identified with it at first, and then re-reading it, as an anthropologist, I realised how ethnocentric it was. I still argue that the most brilliant book was Memoirs of a Young Girl \endash 
 Memoires d\rquote une jeune fille, where she talks about her struggle to escape the bourgeois destiny. Although at the same time she was special, ironically, because her father had become bankrupt, they didn\rquote 
t have any money for a dowry, so she needed to go to university in order to make a good marriage - or she may not make a good marriage. But they wouldn\rquote t have money for a dowry. Caroline, a historian, she\rquote 
s written several books about how often some of the Feminists are from downwardly mobile families. Of course, I was from a downwardly mobile family in a bizarre way. Although I\rquote 
d been to boarding school, my mother was near penniless. Out in my kitchen, I\rquote ve got a sideboard that\rquote s 1950s, and people say, \'93What on earth do you want that thing for?\'94 That was my mother\rquote s pur
chase. She could afford a sideboard, and I\rquote ve got some china \endash  we used to go to Shepherd\rquote s Bush Market, and there were coloured plates, and every week she\rquote d be able to afford to buy another plate, so I\rquote 
ve got red, green, yellow. We used to go with her in the holidays and she\rquote d buy a bowl or something. We were poor. So I don\rquote t know whether I gradually, but I looked back at [Simone de Beauvoir], and I thought, \'93She\rquote 
s talking about how all women belong to nature and men are culture\'94, and I realised from my cro
ss-cultural reading, that this was ethnocentric. But at the same time, the power of that book was that, actually, it was driven by a latent autobiography, because she was talking about her own position. Although she didn\rquote t use the word \'93I\'94
, she used it in her memoirs, but [not] \'93I\'94
 in The Second Sex. But it was the hidden autobiographical power. Just like I was saying with lovely Dennis Marsden, Education and the Working Class, that there it informs, just like when you were saying, how was I sure that the a
pron was this or that? After a while, you, in your bones, you know it \endash  until somebody comes up with a better explanation. But you get the authority. As an anthropologist, you do the writing, you do the research, you\rquote 
re the walking archive, and that\rquote s what I love about that discipline, and that\rquote s why I\rquote ve had several grants where I\rquote ve had to supervise other people, and it\rquote s been a disaster, because it\rquote s not that I\rquote 
ve been dictating, but you choose people, or they beg you to head a grant, and I\rquote ve had two total disasters, they haven\rquote t done a bloody thing, and they\rquote 
ve had huge salaries! And they did nothing! What else could I do? They were the fieldworkers. But what I love is that on the internet, there\rquote s some American professor, and he\rquote s written an absolute r
ave comment about my book, and how wonderful it is, you know. And I was interviewed by these Czech anthropologists, I was given these medals at Pilsen University \endash  the Mayor gave me that. Here are my medals \endash  did I show you them? }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
