\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Yes, well, those two young anthropologists, I mean, they\rquote re brilliant. They\rquote 
ve done work on the gypsies, and they use the word \'93gypsy\'94 in Slovakia, and they found that thing on the internet about - it\rquote s an absolute rave article about my book, and it\rquote 
s been on reading lists and everything. And they love it, that I did this switch back and forth. But the twist is, I said, retrospectively - I remember Jim used to say to me, \'93My God, Judith, you are a fighter!\'94 And he was a very emotio
nal person, and actually tears would come to his eyes, and he\rquote d say, \'93Judith, you are a fighter\'94. I sent the manuscript to Virago, and I don\rquote 
t know whether it was already published or not, but anyway, they then had a deal with a top American publisher \endash  whose name I will remember shortly \endash 
 and Ursula Owen, who had agreed, at every stage, about this writing, then told me that this top American publishers would only accept to publish it in America if I cut out all autobiographical reference \endash  because I was not a celebrity. I said, 
\'93It\rquote s nothing to do with me being a celebrity. I am just an object. I am just an example, because I wasn\rquote t alone. It was de Beauvoir who said, \lquote That book lived because of the enthusiasm through the fifties and the sixties\'94
 - the thousands of letters she got from powerless women. They said, \'93Well, Judith, you\rquote ll lose a lot of money\'94. I mean, they\rquote d pocketed at least \'a35,000 advance from this publisher \endash  I hadn\rquote 
t get a bean of it. And I went, with a wonderful women friend of mine, who\rquote s a professional editor \endash  Marcely Cameron \endash  and she agreed to go with me to Ursula for a meeting, as back up. And I just said, \'93
I refuse to change it. You have had chapter by chapter, and now you expect me to\'94 - the whole point of the book, you know. And the woman kept saying, you know, \'93You will lose a lot of money\'94. I said, \'93I don\rquote t care. I\rquote 
m not in it for the money. I\rquote ve done this thing, and it\rquote s taken me some years\'94. Then she sent me the report. Again, this woman said X, Y and Z. I\rquote d got it wrong. I looked up the French, I\rquote d got it right. The woman claimed I
\rquote d got certain inaccuracies. I went back to the French, and it was dead right \endash  because all these wretched Americans, they\rquote ve all read it in this outrageous translation, and the translation, I may have 
said in my book, is a travesty. The guy was a biologist. They recruited a biologist. They thought it was a sex manual. And he cut out all references to women in history, all lesbians, women poets. He didn\rquote 
t understand what existentialism was or anything. Anyway, there\rquote s this new translation, and I was invited to the launch at Cambridge, and dear Sheila has written the Introduction to the English version, but that\rquote 
s been torn apart by Torrill Moy (?? \endash  68.57), because what they did, they were two Americans living in Paris, and what they\rquote 
ve done is translated according to the idiom they thought was appropriate at the time, instead of updating it. Well, I bought it, but I haven\rquote t read the whole translation, but Sheila told me that Torrill Moy tore it apart, but
 then made incredible references to me, good references to me. Torill Moy was then a lecturer here, she was one of the wives of Terry Eagleton, she was giving lectures on Simone de Beauvoir, and I went up to her afterwards, and I just said, \'93I\rquote 
m writing a book on Simone de Beauvoir\'94. Then she wrote me an ecstatic letter about a year later, saying, \'93My God, you came up and said you were writing a book on Simone de Beauvoir, and it\rquote s come out now, what a fantastic book!\'94
 And I thought, \'93Well, if I\rquote ve got her praising me, I\rquote m fine\'94
. But again, I feel vindicated. The only good thing they did do, which was I had to summarise what the book, so I added a chapter which is a summary of the book, which is a fair point. But then they didn\rquote t have any publicity, any laun
ch, in America, deliberately out of sheer anger, and six months later, they said, \'93It\rquote s hardly sold. It\rquote s going to be pulped. You are entitled to 25 free copies before they\rquote re pulped. And would you agree?\'94
 I gave my address, and the copies never arrived. And they said, \'93Oh, we\rquote re really sorry, we sent them to the wrong address, and so we\rquote ve got none to give you\'94. And they also insisted that the word \'93A Re-Reading\'94 \endash 
 the subtitle \endash  be cut out. And then there\rquote s no money for photographs, I had to scrabble around, \'a3
500 to reproduce one photo. So I scrabbled around with dreadful choice, but I found a wonderful picture of de Beauvoir buying a newspaper from a clearly white working-class woman \endash  a vendor \endash  and I said, \'93
This is one of the few occasions when de Beauvoir met somebody outside her class\'94. Because I said she was - the only people beyond the bourgeoisie was \'93the peasant woman\'94
. The American publisher refused to have that picture in, because they said, \'93In America, we don\rquote t do class\'94. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
