\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 I know! Well, that again, is chance. Peter Riviere (?? \endash 
 sp. 72.38) he was a quite high profile anthropologist on the ESRC, trying to prove anthropology is useful, in the Thatcher days, and he\rquote d been my Internal Examiner for my Ph.D. He\rquote s the one that said, \'93
How on earth did you meet Mr. Busby?\'94 He rang me up, and he said, \'93There\rquote s a whole initiative on ageing\'94, and they were desperate to have an anthropologist get some share of the money. But, of course, suddenly, a person who\rquote 
d done work in Europe was important. So he scrambled around, he, literally, rang me in my office in Essex, and said, \'93Would you like to do something on ageing? There\rquote s this ageing initiative \endash  thousands\'94. And I said, \'93
Well, if I could do anything on France, if I can get to France, I\rquote ll do anything\'94. So I said, \'93I\rquote ll do ageing in France\'94
. And unfortunately, the Board said, this whole utility thing, it had to be useful for Britain, so I could only do a comparative thing, which was ageing in Normandy contrasted with a group in England, otherwise I wouldn\rquote t get the money. So it
\rquote s six months fieldwork in Normandy, and six months in Britain. So, of course, I chose Essex, and Dedham, because I lived there, and I could spin something - I\rquote 
d had access to one neighbour on one side, in her 90s, then probably her 80s. She was a graduate from Edinburgh University, 1918, honestly, the most precise, brilliant woman. I\rquote d meet her every week, go to her house. God, the intell
ect! And then opposite - she was called Muriel Walker - and opposite was Connie, who left school at 12, was a maid. So I had the extremes, and I befriended Connie and Muriel, and I\rquote m still close friends with Connie\rquote 
s niece, who brought up her niece as her daughter, and when Connie died - both Muriel and Connie died within six months of each other \endash  Jan, the niece, inherited the land, which just had a little bungalow in, and she\rquote 
s built two enormous houses on it. So I was able to use them, and I\rquote ve used them
 in articles. But the Normandy thing, again, it fits with my continuous argument that even if you have a brief, and I did keep studying the aged, but the directions it goes, you can\rquote t predict, and you shouldn\rquote t predict, and that\rquote 
s where my reading of Andre Breton, L\rquote Amour fou in 1961, in Paris, the surrealist, brilliant writer, he talked about being \'93disponible\'94, and there he used it about love. It\rquote s a brilliant book, I don\rquote t think it\rquote 
s ever been translated into English, but it\rquote s about wandering, going wand
ering. He wanders through the markets, and he was looking at objects and this, that and the other, and finally he just encountered a woman, and they fell madly in love, and that was how love should be. It was a brilliant romantic book. I transposed that 
\endash  and I\rquote ve got it, again, in my book. To be an anthropologist, you wander. You\rquote re a flaneur or flaneuse. But, of course \'85 and, you know, there\rquote s a whole literature now on \'93flaner\'94
. Keith Tester, whose book I quote, is now a professor at Hull, in sociology \endash  I\rquote ve not met up with him. Then there\rquote s a lot of Feminist writing about the \'93flaneurs\'94
. The flaneur was actually the 19th century gentleman who wandered the streets, but he wasn\rquote t looking for people, he was loving the architecture and the streets and the boulevards, and I said, \'93We wander, but we\rquote 
re open to what comes our way\'94. Another key book I discovered, thank God, in the Department library in Durham, when I was desperate \endash  by the way, they didn\rquote t have any course on methods there. I had to teach theory, 
and I introduced three lectures on methods, and with my Malinowski article, and a diary, and fieldwork, I forcibly introduced methods. And I found Hortense Powdermaker, (?? \endash 
 78.30) Stranger and Friend - that again is the ambiguity about the fieldworker, you\rquote re a stranger, and you become a friend. She was a student of Malinowski, it\rquote 
s just amazing, an utterly brilliant book. I found it on the shelves, along with Return to Laughter, by Eleanor Smith-Bowen, who was really Laura Bohannen. It\rquote ll all be in my book. I\rquote 
ve got these wonderful examples from my anthropologists. It\rquote s just a joy. Nancy \endash  the one who did that picture \endash  she said, \'93Judith, you had that idea in \lquote 95\'94, and she said, \'93Isn\rquote 
t it extraordinary, nobody else has done it\'94. Everybody else has edited books where you have an article, \'93My life with the Malays\'94 or whatever, \'93My life with so and so\'94. I\rquote 
m the only one that has interviewed 22 anthropologists and then been the single author. I\rquote ve cut and pasted hundreds of hours of tape, and cutting out the \'93ums\'94 and \'93you knows\'94
, and it has taken all these years. As an example of my Normandy thing, I don\rquote t know why, David had always made fun of me, he talked about the \'93Normandy Landings\'94, I don\rquote t know why. Because I know I was obsessed with Millet, the painti
ng, and I\rquote 
d been to a Millet exhibition. I love those painters, and I had a big poster in my Durham office, of Millet, The Gleaners. I loved, obviously, French Impressionist painting, and the wonderful thing was that the area of Normandy is where the Impres
sionists, Monet, Pisarro especially, Degas, they did those paintings. So I chose it because of the paintings! The landscape, because I had learned about the landscape through those artists, and also anthropologists had studied the Mediterranean, it was th
e nearest to the exotic, so they\rquote d done Italy, they\rquote d done this. And then there was some French anthropologist who had done Brittany. There was one person who\rquote 
d done inheritance in Brittany or was it a bit of Normandy? But most of Normandy was completely untouched, except for one woman who wrote about witchcraft. But anyway, so I thought, \'93Well, I\rquote 
m going to do Normandy, because this is an untouched area, and yet it\rquote s right near Paris\'94. It is actually called \'93The breadbasket of Paris\'94. They provide all the dairy products. So it\rquote 
s interlinked with the capital. I knew all those things. It\rquote s an hour and a half on the train to Paris, so it wasn\rquote t remote. And then, of course, Flaubert had lived in Normandy So you arrive with all those past readings. I chose an are
a where I knew the literature but not the people. I was at a conference, somewhere in Britain, where there was a French anthropologist, and I said, \'93Oh, I\rquote m going to Normandy\'94, and she said, \'93Oh! I know a professor at Caen University,\'94
 he\rquote s doing village studies. If you go to him, he will place you in a village\'94. I thought, \'93Well, that\rquote s quite an easy entrance\'94
. Anyway, Alan Campbell and I, we decided, in the summer, before my grant started, that we would drive through Normandy to find something, and I visited Caen. I went to this University, I asked for the professor, and the woman said, you know, \'93
Attendez vingt minutes,\'94 - \'93He\rquote ll come in 20 minutes or so\'94, and literally, my knees gave way \endash  this is where the unconscious fits. My knees gave way, and I remembered Susan Rogers, an American who\rquote 
d done work in France, I remember a paper she gave at the American - the \'93Triple A\'94 that\rquote s called \endash  the American Anthropology Association \endash  I mean, there are 2000 anthropologists when you talk, I was in New Orleans in N
ovember, 2000 anthropologists there. It\rquote s just a dream! I go there also because you meet lots of friends and whatever. And I remember her giving a paper about French studies, and she said, \'93The French professors treat you\'94
 - I used it before, earlier, and you picked up that quote, that - \'93you researchers are share croppers, and that you provide the material, and the professor writes it up\'94. And I remembered that. My knees gave way, and I said to the secretary, \'93I
\rquote m sorry. I can\rquote t come. I\rquote ll come back another time\'94. Alan and I drove round Normandy, we\rquote d stay in various B&Bs and places, and we would always go to the Tourist Office, just to find out, but I never said, \'93I\rquote 
m doing research on the aged\'94. Again, you don\rquote t. And we went into, it was Forge les Eaux, w
hich was actually a spa town where the Parisians used to come for their watering, like Bath. It was run down then, I think it was even turned to a swimming pool. And we went into the Tourist Office, and there was this charming young woman called Natalie, 
and I said, \'93I\rquote m taking time off from my lecturing, and I want time to write up, and I\rquote 
m doing some thinking and writing, and I want to perfect my French and get to know people. And can you recommend some lodgings? And what kind of town is this?\'94 And she gave all the spiel, \'93The Parisians came here\'94, and \'93
This hotel was the Great Spa\'94 and whatever. Right at the end she gave me addresses where you could rent a gite, and right at the end, she said, \'93There\rquote s only one problem\'94, - \'93Il n\rquote y a q\rquote une probleme. Il y a
 trop des vieux ici.\'94 (LAUGHS) Too many old people! (LAUGHS) Alan and I went off in euphoria! We went to celebrate in the place, the square, and the mini train came by \endash  I\rquote ve got this in my book \endash 
 a mini train came by, full of grey-haired over-seventies. Of course, France has the highest, the survival rate of the French is extremely high compared to any European country. Apparently the average death rate is 89 or something, and Alan said, \'93
Look, there are your informants!\'94 And then I rented a gite, and Alan went back to teach, because he was at Edinburgh and I was at Essex. Then the next incident about serendipity is that, literally, I dictated \endash  in those days, no mobile phones 
\endash  you\rquote d go to the public Post Office, and you could pay money in advance for a telephone booth, and I literally dictated the last two paragraphs of my de Beauvoir book to Virago, on the phone, and thought, \'93The book\rquote 
s behind me now.\'94 I rented my gite, which was out in the country \endash  a beautiful barn, beautiful converted places. It was the celebration of the Armistice of the First World War, that Sunday, and I thought, \'93Now I\rquote 
m free, I can do fieldwork\'94. I drove, I parked in the town side street, I went to the church, and there were still, in those days, octogenarians, because France cele
brates the First World War, but not the Second, because of the shame of the loss, and also the betrayal, the collaboration. I saw a woman just walking towards the church, and I said, \'93
Excusez moi, je suis anglaise. Est ce que je peux participer a cette ceremonie dans l\rquote eglise?\'94. She said, \'93
Mais, oui. Vous etes anglaise. Mais, bienven ue. Mais allez vous en, mademoiselle. Mais je suis dans le choeur, il faut dire au revoir mademoiselle\'94. So I went into the church, sat obediently at the back, saw all this pro
cession of these lovely 90-year olds, heavy with metal medals and the French flag. And then afterwards they processed out, and there was laying of wreaths at the memorial outside the church, and then a band started up, and then there was a procession to t
he Town Hall. And I stood, a bystander hanging around, and the same woman who saw me, she was in the procession! She said, \'93Alors, venez, mademoiselle, venez avec nous!\'94
 (LAUGHS) And then I processed with the band to the Town Hall. I mean, what a launch! And then we were in the Town Hall, and there was what they call \'93vin d\rquote honneur\'94, you have a toast, and it turned out this woman\rquote 
s husband was Deputy Mayor! (LAUGHS) And she said, \'93Vous etes anglaise\'94, and \'93Tell me why you\rquote re here\'94. And there I didn\rquote t have to hide anything \endash  compared to the gypsies. I just said, \'93I\rquote 
ve studied the aged in England, and I \endash  \'93Je voudrais faire un comparison en Normandie. Et je suis la pour six mois\'94. So she whispered it to her husband, who whispered it to the Mayor, and there were about 50 people there, and he said, \'93
Alors, nous avons avec nous une anglaise professeur, et elle veut etudier les personnes ages dans notre petite ville. Alors, le vin d\rquote honneur a une nglaise!\'94 - and all these 80-year olds lifted their glasses! Then I wa
s swept off for lunch, you know what French lunches are! We went to her sister-in-law. I was driven around the country, I was put down to my gite at midnight. Now, this is what I mean about being \'93disponible\'94. My fieldwork was launched. }{
