\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Yes. Wonderful woman. I know. I said there were urban clubs \endash  and I\rquote ve written on that \endash 
 because Mitterand was giving loads of money for clubs at that point, very clever idea, of course. You imagine Cameron doing that! So everybody was setting up little clubs. The one in Forges les Eaux was totally dominated by the bourgeo
isie, and a lot of the retired so-called peasants, they were brought to the Maison de Retraite, and they suddenly found themselves being dictated to by their former schoolteachers, who were telling them how to sing. But anyway, I thought, \'93
Well, there are clubs in rural areas\'94. And somebody, I can\rquote t remember, said, \'93Madame Gregoire, in this tiny village, she is Presidente of the local club\'94. I went, drove round there, and she wasn\rquote 
t there, just her husband, and I said, \'93Est ce que je peut venir, je suis interessee dans les personnes ages\'94. It was always good to say, \'93comparing with England\'94, so you weren\rquote 
t just objectifying them. Then finally I arrived, and it was the afternoon, and it was a beautiful building with the old wooden panels, like Elizabethan \endash  t
he old barns. There she was, she was unusual because she was six foot tall, her husband was probably about 5\rquote  6\'94 - and I went in, and there again, questionnaires were a mode of entry. It was useful to say, \'93Can I interview you?\'94
 as a strategy. And she invited me in, and she was plucking a chicken, and all the way through, she was answering me, you know, \'93How many people?\'94 \'93What do you do?\'94
 What they loved was having coach trips to Rouen or something like that, you know \endash  not reading groups \endash  and she said she objected to all this singing and whatever, that these people wanted adventure, and it\rquote 
s absolutely right. And having plucked the chicken, and me having asked these questions, she said, \'93J\rquote ai du travail a faire\'94. I thought, \'93Well, bloody hell, you\rquote ve been doing work all the way through!\'94
 (LAUGHS) And then she said, \'93Je vais traire les vaches\'94. I said, \'93Est ce que je peux venir?\'94 \'93Vous etes professeure \endash  venez, venez!\'94 Then she went into this [barn]. This was December, God it was cold! It was wonderful! And
 she opened the doors of this barn, and the heat of these cows just hit the air. There were maybe 13 cows in there. There were old swallows nests, it was just amazing! She started hand-milking, and I\rquote ve got a picture in that book \endash 
 Alan took the picture, he came back later to take pictures. And I was talking to her as she was hand-milking, and what I learnt from being with Hugh, which is, \'93Can I help?\'94 This old trick! Wonderful! And I said, \'93 Est ce que je peux faire ca?
\'94 And this eyebrow shot up again, \'93What is this professor doing with manual labour?\'94 Because I met up with a French anthropologist a year later, for a big event in Paris, and I will remember her name later, she\rquote 
d done work on the peasant in Brittany, but it was mainly 19th century history, and I said I was learning to milk cows, and she was just staggered! \'93Mais, pourquoi? Qu\rquote est ce que vous pouvez apprendre avec ca?\'94
 So you learnt that the French didn\rquote t do manual physical work. Their fieldwork was tres intellectuel, you know. Anyway, so she said - I\rquote 
ve repeated this, I lectured in Brunel last year, and there were a couple of French people in the audience, and they were absolutely delighted, and they loved me speaking French and I still get ecstatic e-mails from them, just from that one lecture
! And she said, \'93Alors c\rquote est une vache un peu en colere, il faut attendre. Il faut avoir Mere No-no\'93 \endash \'93Mother No-no\'94. She had names for them all! (LAUGHS) And she took me, and she said, \'93Mere No-no, c\rquote est Judith\'94
, and Madame No-no turned her head round, \'93Il faut introduire. Judith, c\rquote est Mere No-no\'94. So we were introduced (LAUGHS). Then she was very worried. I\rquote 
ve still got my Jaeger duffel coat that I bought in 1976, in Oxford, and I was wearing that, and she was terribly worried about any dirt. And then th
e three-legged stool. I was really angry because I had a three-legged stool in my office in Hull, and I used it for my inaugural lecture. I put it in front, and I said, \'93This is my anthropological chair \endash  my milking stool\'94
, but some bastard stole it from my office. I started, and again, it\rquote s whether you can do things. Nothing came out. It\rquote s delicate. You can\rquote t just pull. And then she said, \'93Attendez, je reviens.\'94
 And then she came back with a flash camera, and she took a photograph of me. And I said, \'93Isn\rquote t this wonderful, the return of the gaze\'94
. It was, you know, in those days, developed in the local chemist, and I got copies, and I use it again and again as an example that the person was so amazed that the anthropologist was doing this. It was just incred
ible. And that was a breakthrough. Then right at the end of the day of the milking, she had all these buckets, and a container, and she said, \'93Buvez!\'94 And she got a glass, and \'93Alors, c\rquote est ;pure. Il n\rquote y a pas de concentre\'94 
\endash  \'93My grass doesn\rquote t have pesticide. This is pure milk\'94. That\rquote s when I said I was drinking the landscape. Honestly, I went back to my gite in a total buzz. I just thought, \'93My God, this is it, you know\'94
. I was like her adopted daughter! }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
