\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
It changed because I listened to her views about landscape. It fitted in with my ideas about Pisarro, that she had a consciousness of landscape, and I\rquote m very pleased because I used those ideas in my inaugural lecture at 
Hull years later. The ESRC rubbish me because I hadn\rquote t written a monograph on that French material. I was far too ambitious. I thought, for one year, I\rquote d do one monograph on my fieldwork, and one on Normandy. (a) I didn\rquote 
t have enough time \endash  only six months \endash  I had to come back to Dedham. I didn\rquote 
t have enough for a monograph, but in that research one-year, I put in for money for a camera, and I went back, with a cine camera, and I filmed her talking about the landscape, and what I was inspired by, in a funny way, was I\rquote 
d started reading books on landscape, an edited book that came out about the time I came back from France, edited by Eric Hirsch (?? \endash  sp.) who\rquote s at Brunel, and I\rquote 
ve now co-edited a book with him, Knowing How to Know. And he did something on landscape, but the real woman behind that is a Guyanese Indian, she\rquote s absolutely brilliant that woman. She\rquote 
s the force. And Fabian had written a book called, Time and the Other. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
