. Then the anthropologists were so brilliant that they squeezed all - because I actually had my chapters, my lectures at Essex, recorded. I remember now, I tape-recorded them, my last year. I don\rquote 
t know whether I was thinking of a book then, but I know Richard Wilson rang me later. I gave a paper in Belfast at the ASA last April, and the whole theme was \'93the interview\'94, and I caused an uproar in some ways \endash 
 the questions were incredible. I said I deliberately chose people I knew, I broke all the rules, it was no good interviewing strangers. In fact, there was one Australian woman, who I won\rquote t name \endash  she was visiting Oxford \endash 
 I took her back to my house when I lived off the Abingdon Road, and I interviewed her, and she was totally uptight, she couldn\rquote t answer a thing. And I realised it didn\rquote t work with people you didn\rquote t know - they were too nervous 
\endash  even though you had an informal atmosphere. And I gave this paper where I said that I broke all the rules about interviewing, although inspired also by Ann Oakley, the wonderful article on \'93Interviewing Women\'94 \endash  I don\rquote 
t know if you know that one? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
