\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
In anthropology, you had to do a two-year B.Litt. before you even started on fieldwork. So they were funding five years, because it was also for people who hadn\rquote t got an undergraduate degree. Malcolm did two years\rquote 
 work, library work, on Ghana, on the Ashanti, then he went off to Ghana, and he said that, \'93Really, what hooked me, was the material culture \endash  the incredible sculpture, the weaving, everything\'94. He said, \'93I was just absolutely mesmerised
 by that, and I started doing that\'94. And then there\rquote 
s wonderful stories of him. And he was there for a year or two, and then to extend his time, he had a year lecturing at the university with all these amazing exchanges. He came back, and it was at least f
ive years since he first met the French anthropologist. The French anthropologist was back there in Oxford, and and Malcolm said, \'93Oh\'94, you know, \'93I didn\rquote t really take to your suggestion to look at the Ashanti and witchcraft,\'94
 there is some witchcraft, but he said it didn\rquote t really, \'93I didn\rquote t follow your advice, but I did go to the Ashanti. I concentrated on material culture and religious cults\'94. And the guy said, \'93I didn\rquote t say \lquote The Ashanti
\rquote , I said, \lquote The Azandi\rquote \'94. So there was a Freudian mis-hearing. His wh
ole project was misinterpreted, because nobody could believe that a French anthropologist would have the audacity to say, with the world expert on Azandi, you should go and study the Azandi. You know! Fancy telling Evans-Pritchard, \'93
Your student should go and study the Azandi like you did\'94. So there was a wonderful mis-hearing. Malcolm became the Curator of the first Museum of Mankind. His whole thing was launched through a mis-hearing! (LAUGHS) }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
