\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Mmm. Yeah. Mmm. And there are two or three of them that I do say, I haven\rquote t quoted them, but 
ironically, the one - I did have a cobbled interview with Alan, when he was visiting me in Oxford, oh, I don\rquote t know, in 2004 or something, and he has a very Highland accent \endash  which I can understand \endash 
 but when I sent it to the transcriber, she said she couldn\rquote t understand a word! (LAUGHS) So it was never transcribed! She couldn\rquote t understand a word of the tutor! (LAUGHS) But I will use it in something else, but I haven\rquote 
t got time to listen to the whole thing and copy word for word, it\rquote s just too late now. But I sent it to her, a year or two ago, and she just said she couldn\rquote t understand a word. And she said, \'93If you listen, you\rquote ll see what I mean
\'94. Well I lived with the man for some years, so I should be able to know what he was saying! I mean, the secretaries in Edinburgh, when they met Alan, they said, \'93My God! He\rquote s a Highlander! A tutor!\'94
 They thought these guys should hide their accent! They thought, down in elite middle-class Edinburgh, that you\rquote d never talk with a Highlander accent. They thought it was co
mical! But I did deliberately, in the end, choose people who were of different ethnicities, you know, or different backgrounds. Like Professor Talib. I got to know him because I was supervising this Egyptian student, still at Hull I was, and he\rquote 
d just been appointed, and he was giving wonderful lectures on Islam, and so I went to his lectures and, honestly, it was a few months after 9/11, and I was totally shocked. I mean, there were four other people attending the lecture and he\rquote 
d done such work. He thought he was coming to the centre of the universe and then there were four undergraduates asking inane questions at the end. He was, \'93Who are you?\'94 and, you know, \'93Have tea with me\'94. I said, \'93Well, I\rquote 
m coming here because I\rquote m supervising a student who\rquote s with the Bedouin in Sinai Desert, and he\rquote s writing a lot more on Islam\'94. In fact, dear Heysham, I don\rquote t know whether he was Shi\rquote 
ar or Sunni, but he converted to Sufism after being with the Bedouin, where you\rquote re allowed to have music. So that was how I got to know Talib. Then dear Helena, who\rquote 
s got a Senegalese father and a French mother, but she was brought up in France, and she was a professional dancer before she took to anthropology, she heard my lecture when I talked about free association, and the hall was p
acked, and they loved my jokes. She said, \'93You\rquote re my favourite lecturer\'94, and she would make contact. I had lunch with her just a week ago. But she\rquote s one of those who\rquote s totally overworked, ground down. Ground down. }{
