\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
I loved the fact that they were State School students. It was an inspiration. No Etonians. You were teaching first generation State School. And because it was technically sociology/anthropology, most of them had come in with \lquote A\rquote 
 Levels in sociology, but th
ere was a wonderful scheme because you had to do the ethnographic survey, I think it was called, the first year compulsory course. Anybody doing sociology or Joint Degree had to do that course. And they all got turned on to anthropology. They\rquote 
d never heard of it, you know. And they then switched to doing it \endash  there wasn\rquote t a single Honours anthropology course, but they were absolutely thrilled. And that was the joy \endash  teaching - and my most wonderful triumph, in a way, was 
\'85 I used to say, even from Durham, I could recognise which essays were written by men and which were women. I set a discussion, \'93Discuss some of the challenges of studying a culture other than your own\'94
. The men would talk about clashing cosmologies and religious systems, and the women would talk about body language and eye contact, very down to earth specific. And I thought, \'93Could there be a combination of the two?\'94 I\rquote 
ve come up with a theory of that, which I won\rquote t give you, but I then taught a course I was very proud of, called \'93Visualism in Anthropology\'94, which was museums, photography, film, landscape, and the body in Western art. That year, there were 
\endash  again, it was feminised \endash  there were only two men doing the course, and they hardly appeared. And it was anonymous marking, and I read t
hese brilliant scripts, and I said to my co-marker, Peter Foster, who I adored, but tragically he died within a year of a heart attack. I said, \'93You know, I can\rquote 
t understand it, because I might as well not give lectures, because this is clearly written by a man. It\rquote s got this brilliant abstract, but then also very specific little examples\'94. I said, \'93This really throws me, because it\rquote 
s clearly written by a male. I know these two idle boys never attended half my tutorials or anything. Anyway, when it came to 
the Examination Board, this same number had Firsts in everything, and then you finally reveal the name. It was a woman who [had a] Pakistani father, Irish mother, and she told me her life story. I said, \'93You\rquote ve got to carry on with this work\'94
. She had been subject to racism in Stoke-on-Trent. She was brought up, and people would say, \'93Why is your skin dirty?\'94 There were no Asians, let alone Caribbeans there! Her parents just didn\rquote t know how to handle it and said, \'93
Put up with it\'94. So she dropped out of school at 16. She disappeared. She took to heroin. She slept under railway bridges. What a story! One day, she was begging, and a man said, \'93What about you, Asian bitch\'94
, or something. She was high on heroin and she got up and hit him, and then she was taken to court, and she was found guilty of not just assault, and she was sent to prison. She didn\rquote 
t know you could have Legal Aid or anything. She did a year or two in prison, and then she came out and thought, \'93I\rquote ve got to get going\'94. And she went to evening class, she did \lquote A\rquote  Level sociology. And, of course, we didn
\rquote t attract - we had phone ins, for people who had got low \lquote A\rquote  Levels, that\rquote s how we recruited students who\rquote d been dropped out of other universities. And she said, \'93I couldn\rquote t believe it, Mark\'94 \endash  my c
olleague \endash  \'93accepted me, and I\rquote d only got two \lquote A\rquote  Levels\'94. Then she said, \'93I couldn\rquote t believe it when we did anthropology. My difference was being celebrated!\'94
 We were celebrating difference. And then I said, \'93You didn\rquote t fit into any of my categories\'94. She said, \'93Judith, that\rquote s the story of my life\'94. So I say that Hull was inspiring for the undergrads. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 And then it finished, because they closed the Department. ... }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
