\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Of course, we got a 3A or a 3B, but, you see, in anthropology, there\rquote s only 1
2 Departments, there are 120 Sociology Departments, so they have to give 3Bs to some anthropology. They realised they\rquote 
d made a terrible mistake, but it was too late. We lost eight tenured positions. People were snapped up. Three people were snapped up for Chairs. If we were so low \endash  one in Melbourne, two in Sheffield \endash 
 200 applicants for a lectureship in Manchester, one of our students was snapped up there. Two deaths, two retirements and so there were three members of the Department left. Of course, the De
an knew that if he could get me to take early retirement, that would be the death knell. But I knew there was no hope. We were not going to get eight [appointments], they were reappointing criminologists and sociologists. I thought, \'93I\rquote 
m not going to write mission statements for a Department that once had 12 and has now got three.\'94
 But it was partly, again, politics, that ambition and greed overcomes. The Dean was terrified of this woman who threw a tantrum, and I was excluded from all discussion, and I could see the mistakes. And, of course, I was proven right, but I didn\rquote 
t want to be proven right. And she didn\rquote t get a personal chair out of it, so she went off somewhere else. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
