\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Well, I think the best thing was discovering anthropology. And there was one thing I wanted to say, but we haven\rquote 
t got room, which is, just briefly, my mother 
had Caribbean lodgers in our house from the late fifties, after my grandmother died. She was so shocked seeing the way that Afrikaans treated Africans when she was there, and when my grandmother died, we had the middle part of the flat vacant - it was a f
lat, though with a shared bathroom. My mother had some Australians and they proved to be a nightmare, and then she rang up the British Council \endash  and I said I\rquote m very proud of her. I suppose that\rquote 
s it, I was lucky to have my mother. They said, in those days, they said, \'93Do you mind coloured people?\'94 And she said, \'93I prefer them. They\rquote re so much more civilised\'94
. So we had a string of Jamaicans, Trinidadians, in our house, causing uproar in the neighbourhood \endash  white suburban neighbourhood. Some of them worked in
 the Embassy, others were telephonists. So I was also brought up with a total being at ease with people from other cultures, to the shock of the neighbourhood! \'93My God, you even share a bathroom with them?\'94
 And other things, I think back, things like meeting Malcolm X at the Union, and I had a relationship with a famous Jamaican here. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Oh, did you? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
\par 
\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Mmm. Yeah. Eric Abrahams. I walked into the Union with a friend, Trinidadian, who looked like Jimi Hendrix, and I\rquote 
d already gone to hear the first New Year speakers at the Union, because the new members were allowed to sort of debate, and there was this brilliant speaker, and it was Eric, and I went up to him, and I said, \'93My God, you\rquote re a professional\'94
. He was a Rhodes Scholar \endash  I didn\rquote t know any of this. And then a year later, we were at a conference in Cambridge, or maybe it was before, he said, \'93
Do you know, I was so happy when you walked in with that guy, Ken, because I knew you weren\rquote t racist\'94. And the idea, now, that people should think it s
hocking that a white woman should walk into the Union with a black guy, who was a post-graduate in philosophy - he was originally a journalist, and he thinks A.J. Ayer secretly paid for his fees, because A.J. Ayer met him in Trinidad. Ken had said he want
ed to do philosophy, and suddenly there was an anonymous donation, and he was paid for to do a Ph.D. at Oxford. And I said, \'93Come and see the Union\'94, and Eric said to me, you know, \'93I knew you weren\rquote t prejudiced\'94
. And then the irony was that it turned out later, that his two sisters went to my school! (LAUGHS) }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 I think that\rquote s a great point to stop really! }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 
