\par Judith:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4982948\charrsid4982948 Yes! But I looked him up, I\rquote ve looked him up, if you Google, there\rquote s the famous Jamaicans, and I can\rquote 
t believe it, because he became Minister, and he was the first Caribbean who was employed by the BBC, and he became President of the Union \endash  the first black guy President of the Union \endash  and he definitely engineered Malcolm X\rquote 
s visit. Then Malcolm X, I met him, and then he sent word that he wanted me to meet him, and I had a meeting with him in the Randolph Hotel. He said, \'93You must have another woman with you\'94
. I spent three hours in his company, and that was December, and he was assassinated in February. And I\rquote ve got a wonderful letter that says \endash  to the African student that arranged him \endash  said \'93
Please send my best wishes to Judith, how I enjoyed talking to her, and her sense of humour\'94. I\rquote ve got that letter upstairs. I\rquote ve got his signature and his address, that he wrote for me. So it\rquote s not ju
st celebrity. But I remember I went back, I just ran down the corridor at St. Hilda\rquote s saying, you know, \'93Anybody join me to go to the Randolph in half an hour\'94. Sheila wasn\rquote t there, and so and so wasn\rquote 
t there, and Chloe Stallybrass, who wasn\rquote t much into politics, but she was Labour, she said, \'93I\rquote ll come along\'94. And we had a meeting about five years ago, where we tape-recorded our reminiscencs of what happened in that major event. }{
